1
00:00:05,420 --> 00:00:06,136
<i>[POLICE WHISTLE BLOWING]</i>

2
00:00:06,700 --> 00:00:08,213
<i>[ALARM RINGING]</i>

3
00:00:08,300 --> 00:00:10,131
<i>[POLICE SIREN WAILING]</i>

4
00:00:18,540 --> 00:00:20,496
<i>[AMBULANCE SIREN WAILING]</i>

5
00:01:01,540 --> 00:01:05,419
<i>MAN: Police Constable Nicholas Angel.
Born and schooled in London.</i>

6
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:11,052
<i>Graduated Canterbury University in 1993
with a double first in politics and sociology.</i>

7
00:01:11,140 --> 00:01:13,415
<i>Attended Hendon College of Police Training.</i>

8
00:01:14,660 --> 00:01:17,220
<i>Displayed great aptitude in field exercises.</i>

9
00:01:19,580 --> 00:01:22,174
<i>Notably, urban pacification and riot control.</i>

10
00:01:22,700 --> 00:01:23,769
Back off!

11
00:01:23,860 --> 00:01:27,933
<i>Academically excelled in theoretical
course work and final year examinations.</i>

12
00:01:28,340 --> 00:01:30,251
<i>Received the Baton of Honour.</i>

13
00:01:30,340 --> 00:01:34,219
<i>Graduated with distinction into
the Metropolitan Police Service.</i>

14
00:01:34,660 --> 00:01:38,175
<i>Quickly established an effectiveness
and popularity within the community.</i>

15
00:01:38,540 --> 00:01:39,655
Use your brain.

16
00:01:40,060 --> 00:01:42,972
<i>Proceeded to improve skill base
with courses in advanced driving</i>

17
00:01:44,660 --> 00:01:46,855
<i>and advanced cycling.</i>

18
00:01:47,980 --> 00:01:51,450
<i>Became heavily involved
in a number of extra vocational activities.</i>

19
00:01:51,540 --> 00:01:54,418
<i>To this day holds the Met record
for the 100 metre dash.</i>

20
00:01:55,300 --> 00:02:00,135
<i>In 2001 began active duty with
the renowned SO 19 armed response unit.</i>

21
00:02:00,260 --> 00:02:04,412
<i>Received a bravery award for efforts
in the resolution of Operation Crackdown.</i>

22
00:02:04,900 --> 00:02:08,290
<i>In the last 12 months
has received nine special commendations.</i>

23
00:02:08,500 --> 00:02:11,412
<i>Achieved the highest arrest record
for any officer in the Met.</i>

24
00:02:11,500 --> 00:02:13,968
<i>And sustained three injuries
in the line of duty.</i>

25
00:02:14,060 --> 00:02:18,690
<i>Most recently in December when wounded
by a man dressed as Father Christmas.</i>

26
00:02:21,160 --> 00:02:23,260
- Hello, Nicholas.
- Hello, Sergeant.

27
00:02:23,760 --> 00:02:26,260
- How's the hand?
- Still a bit stiff.

28
00:02:27,260 --> 00:02:28,249
It can get awfully hairy out there.

29
00:02:28,980 --> 00:02:32,450
I'm surprised you weren't snapped up
sooner for a nice desk job. That's what I did.

30
00:02:32,540 --> 00:02:34,735
I prefer to think my office is
out on the street.

31
00:02:34,820 --> 00:02:36,299
Indeed, you do.

32
00:02:36,580 --> 00:02:40,858
Your arrest record is 400% higher
than any other officer.

33
00:02:40,940 --> 00:02:45,377
Which is why it's high time
that such skills were put to better use.

34
00:02:47,220 --> 00:02:49,529
- We're making you Sergeant.
- I see.

35
00:02:50,300 --> 00:02:52,018
In Sandford, Gloucestershire.

36
00:02:52,100 --> 00:02:54,660
- In where, sorry?
- In Sandford, Gloucestershire.

37
00:02:54,740 --> 00:02:57,698
- That's in the country.
- Yes, lovely.

38
00:02:58,500 --> 00:03:00,252
Isn't there a Sergeant's position
here in London?

39
00:03:00,340 --> 00:03:01,489
No.

40
00:03:01,580 --> 00:03:03,775
- Can I remain here as a PC?
- No.

41
00:03:03,860 --> 00:03:06,169
- Do I have any choice in this?
- No.

42
00:03:07,220 --> 00:03:08,892
Sergeant, I kind of like it here.

43
00:03:08,980 --> 00:03:11,016
Well, you've always wanted
to transfer to the country.

44
00:03:11,100 --> 00:03:13,694
- In 20 years or so, yes.
- Well done, you.

45
00:03:14,180 --> 00:03:15,818
Hang on, I don't remember telling you that.

46
00:03:15,900 --> 00:03:17,891
Yes, you did. You said,

47
00:03:17,980 --> 00:03:20,858
"I'd love to settle down
in the country sometime, Janine."

48
00:03:22,180 --> 00:03:23,772
I'd like to talk to the Inspector.

49
00:03:23,860 --> 00:03:25,737
You can speak to the Inspector,
but I can promise you

50
00:03:25,820 --> 00:03:28,653
he will tell you
exactly the same thing as I have.

51
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:33,610
- Hello, Nicholas. How's the hand?
- It's still a bit stiff.

52
00:03:33,700 --> 00:03:36,009
- And how are things at home?
- I'm sorry, sir?

53
00:03:36,100 --> 00:03:37,533
How's Janine?

54
00:03:39,140 --> 00:03:40,858
We're no longer together, sir.

55
00:03:40,940 --> 00:03:43,738
- Right. Then where are you living?
- He's staying at the Section House, sir.

56
00:03:43,820 --> 00:03:46,653
- With the recruits?
- Yes, he's living out of cardboard boxes.

57
00:03:46,740 --> 00:03:48,537
Well, then, you're packed already.

58
00:03:48,620 --> 00:03:51,453
Nicholas, we're offering you a smashing
position with a delightful cottage,

59
00:03:51,540 --> 00:03:54,816
in a lovely little place
that I think has won Village of the Year

60
00:03:54,900 --> 00:03:58,131
I don't know how many times.
It'll be good for you.

61
00:03:58,340 --> 00:04:01,650
- I don't really know what to say.
- Yes?

62
00:04:01,940 --> 00:04:03,453
Yes, thank you.

63
00:04:05,940 --> 00:04:07,658
No, I'm sorry. I'm gonna have to...

64
00:04:07,740 --> 00:04:10,538
- You want to take this higher?
- Yes, yes, I do.

65
00:04:10,620 --> 00:04:12,451
You want me to bother
the Chief Inspector with this?

66
00:04:12,540 --> 00:04:13,575
Yes.

67
00:04:13,660 --> 00:04:16,572
You want me to get the Chief Inspector
to come all the way down here?

68
00:04:16,660 --> 00:04:19,128
- Yes, I do.
- Okay.

69
00:04:20,020 --> 00:04:21,169
Kenneth!

70
00:04:21,660 --> 00:04:24,857
- Hello, Nicholas. How's the hand?
- Still a bit stiff.

71
00:04:25,220 --> 00:04:26,812
- Chief Inspector...
- Keep your seat.

72
00:04:26,900 --> 00:04:29,016
Now, I know what you're going to say,

73
00:04:29,100 --> 00:04:32,251
but the fact is,
you've been making us all look bad.

74
00:04:32,340 --> 00:04:33,375
I'm sorry, sir?

75
00:04:33,460 --> 00:04:34,859
Of course we all appreciate your efforts,

76
00:04:34,940 --> 00:04:37,408
but you've been rather
letting the side down.

77
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:39,377
It's all about being a team player, Nicholas.

78
00:04:39,460 --> 00:04:41,371
You can't be the Sheriff of London.

79
00:04:41,460 --> 00:04:43,178
If we let you carry on running round town,

80
00:04:43,260 --> 00:04:46,935
you'll continue to be exceptional
and we can't have that.

81
00:04:47,020 --> 00:04:49,295
You'll put us all out of a job.

82
00:04:49,660 --> 00:04:51,298
With respect, sir.

83
00:04:51,380 --> 00:04:56,500
- You can't just make people disappear.
- Yes, I can. I'm the Chief Inspector.

84
00:04:57,180 --> 00:05:01,571
Well, however you spin this, there's
one thing you haven't taken into account.

85
00:05:01,700 --> 00:05:04,089
And that's what the "team"
is gonna make of this.

86
00:05:14,940 --> 00:05:16,771
[CELL PHONE VIBRATING]

87
00:05:16,940 --> 00:05:18,089
[SIGHS]

88
00:05:18,980 --> 00:05:20,891
<i>- Hello?
- ANGEL: Janine, it's me.</i>

89
00:05:20,980 --> 00:05:22,936
I know. I'm at work.

90
00:05:23,020 --> 00:05:24,851
<i>I know, I'm outside.</i>

91
00:05:26,580 --> 00:05:28,252
What's the situation?

92
00:05:28,340 --> 00:05:31,298
You know the situation.
We've been over this.

93
00:05:31,380 --> 00:05:32,733
No, I... I meant here.

94
00:05:32,820 --> 00:05:35,334
Two people involved,
distinct signs of a struggle.

95
00:05:35,420 --> 00:05:36,569
Complete mess.

96
00:05:36,660 --> 00:05:39,618
- You are talking about here?
- Nicholas, what do you want?

97
00:05:39,700 --> 00:05:43,693
Well, I have something important to tell you
and I didn't wanna do it over the phone.

98
00:05:45,780 --> 00:05:48,499
Janine, I've been transferred.
I'm moving away for a while.

99
00:05:48,660 --> 00:05:49,695
I'm not Janine.

100
00:05:49,780 --> 00:05:50,974
[JANINE CLEARS THROAT]

101
00:05:51,060 --> 00:05:53,494
Janine, I've been transferred.
I'm moving away for a while.

102
00:05:53,580 --> 00:05:55,252
I know. Bob told me.

103
00:05:55,340 --> 00:05:56,455
Hello, there.

104
00:05:56,540 --> 00:05:58,531
Well, I wanted to tell you in person.

105
00:05:58,620 --> 00:06:00,656
And there's no reason
we can't be civil with each other.

106
00:06:00,740 --> 00:06:02,492
It's not that long ago
we were talking about getting married.

107
00:06:02,580 --> 00:06:05,378
Yes, but you were already married
to the force, weren't you?

108
00:06:05,460 --> 00:06:07,178
We're actually supposed to call it
"the service" now.

109
00:06:07,260 --> 00:06:09,854
Official vocab guidelines state
that "force" is too aggressive.

110
00:06:09,940 --> 00:06:11,658
See. It's only ever about the job.

111
00:06:11,740 --> 00:06:13,856
- It's all you care about.
- That's not true.

112
00:06:13,940 --> 00:06:16,738
No, you're right,
you do have that rubber plant.

113
00:06:16,820 --> 00:06:20,415
- It's a Japanese Peace Lily.
- You just can't switch off, Nicholas.

114
00:06:21,140 --> 00:06:26,089
And until you find a person you care
about more than your job, you never will.

115
00:06:26,980 --> 00:06:29,972
Besides, you were the one
who suggested we take a break.

116
00:06:30,060 --> 00:06:33,894
Yes, well,
guilty people often make the first move.

117
00:06:35,020 --> 00:06:36,976
Actually, there's something
I need to tell you.

118
00:06:37,060 --> 00:06:39,415
- You're seeing someone else.
- Yes. How did you...

119
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:41,411
- Is it Bob?
- No.

120
00:06:41,500 --> 00:06:44,856
Does Bob look like
the kind of person I'd go out with?

121
00:06:44,940 --> 00:06:46,373
It's Dave.

122
00:06:46,460 --> 00:06:47,859
Hello, there.

123
00:06:48,740 --> 00:06:50,139
I see.

124
00:06:51,140 --> 00:06:52,573
Oh, Nicholas.

125
00:06:52,820 --> 00:06:55,334
You do realise that window
was broken from the inside?

126
00:06:55,780 --> 00:06:57,532
<i>[HELICOPTER WHIRRING]</i>

127
00:07:02,900 --> 00:07:04,299
<i>FRANK: Hello there, Nicholas,
Frank Butterman here, your new Inspector.</i>

128
00:07:04,380 --> 00:07:07,452
<i>I'm just calling with details
of your accommodation.</i>

129
00:07:07,540 --> 00:07:10,498
<i>We've got you a lovely little cottage
on Spencer Hill.</i>

130
00:07:11,060 --> 00:07:13,369
<i>Look forward to meeting you anon. Cheerio.</i>

131
00:07:14,500 --> 00:07:17,492
<i>Nicholas, Frank again.
One other thing about your cottage.</i>

132
00:07:17,820 --> 00:07:18,889
<i>It's not ready.</i>

133
00:07:54,340 --> 00:07:55,568
[SNORING]

134
00:07:58,700 --> 00:08:02,215
It would appear the heavens have opened.

135
00:08:09,020 --> 00:08:12,854
- I was hoping to check in.
- Check in?

136
00:08:13,340 --> 00:08:15,570
But you've always been here.

137
00:08:15,940 --> 00:08:19,728
- Excuse me?
- Oh, I'm sorry.

138
00:08:19,820 --> 00:08:21,492
I thought you were my husband.

139
00:08:21,580 --> 00:08:24,174
- You must be Sergeant Angel.
- Yes, I am.

140
00:08:24,260 --> 00:08:27,411
I'm Joyce Cooper.
I trust you had a pleasant trip. Fascist.

141
00:08:27,900 --> 00:08:29,174
I beg your pardon?

142
00:08:29,260 --> 00:08:34,288
"System of Government characterised
by extreme dictatorship." Seven across.

143
00:08:34,740 --> 00:08:39,097
- Oh, I see. It's "fascism."
- Fascism. Wonderful.

144
00:08:39,340 --> 00:08:43,572
Now, we've put you in the Castle Suite.
Bernard will escort you up there.

145
00:08:44,860 --> 00:08:48,739
Well, actually,
I could probably make my own way up. Hag.

146
00:08:49,180 --> 00:08:50,898
I beg your pardon?

147
00:08:50,980 --> 00:08:54,609
"Evil old woman considered
frightful or ugly." It's 12 down.

148
00:08:54,860 --> 00:08:57,249
Oh, bless you.

149
00:09:40,900 --> 00:09:44,370
- Pint of lager, please, Mary.
- MARY: Right you are, my love.

150
00:09:44,860 --> 00:09:46,532
Yes, sir, what can I get you?

151
00:09:46,620 --> 00:09:51,330
Could I have a glass
of the cranberry juice, please?

152
00:09:51,420 --> 00:09:52,648
Certainly.

153
00:09:52,740 --> 00:09:56,050
Now, you wouldn't, by any chance,
be the new policeman?

154
00:09:56,140 --> 00:09:58,096
Police officer, yes. I'm Nicholas Angel.

155
00:09:58,180 --> 00:10:00,933
- I'm Roy Porter. This is my wife Mary.
- Mary.

156
00:10:01,460 --> 00:10:02,654
MARY: Welcome to Sandford.

157
00:10:02,740 --> 00:10:04,173
If there's anything you need,
just let us know.

158
00:10:04,260 --> 00:10:07,411
Thank you. Could I borrow your newspaper?

159
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:08,694
It's not ours, love.

160
00:10:08,780 --> 00:10:11,248
We're not big fans of the local fish wrapper,
are we, Mare?

161
00:10:11,340 --> 00:10:14,776
- They listed her age as 55.
- When I'm actually 53.

162
00:10:14,860 --> 00:10:16,054
Fifty-three.

163
00:10:16,140 --> 00:10:17,368
[GROANS]

164
00:10:17,460 --> 00:10:20,657
- Pint of lager, please, Mary.
- Right you are, my love.

165
00:10:25,220 --> 00:10:26,812
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

166
00:10:52,180 --> 00:10:54,136
- Excuse me.
- What?

167
00:10:54,220 --> 00:10:56,529
- When's your birthday?
- Twenty-second of February.

168
00:10:56,620 --> 00:10:58,531
- What year?
- Every year.

169
00:10:58,620 --> 00:10:59,689
Get out.

170
00:11:00,820 --> 00:11:05,814
- When's your birthday?
- Eighth of May, 1969.

171
00:11:05,900 --> 00:11:07,618
- You're 37?
- Yeah.

172
00:11:07,700 --> 00:11:08,769
Get out.

173
00:11:08,860 --> 00:11:09,929
When's your birthday?

174
00:11:10,020 --> 00:11:11,055
[STAMMERING]

175
00:11:11,140 --> 00:11:12,209
Out.

176
00:11:12,700 --> 00:11:15,737
- Is there a problem, Officer?
- Yes, there is, Mr Porter.

177
00:11:15,820 --> 00:11:18,493
It would appear a number
of your patrons are under age.

178
00:11:18,580 --> 00:11:21,174
Well, a few of them may be
a month or two south of proper.

179
00:11:21,260 --> 00:11:23,899
But if they're in here,
it stops them getting into trouble out there.

180
00:11:23,980 --> 00:11:26,130
Yeah, the way we see it,
it's all for the greater good.

181
00:11:26,220 --> 00:11:27,289
The greater good.

182
00:11:27,380 --> 00:11:31,498
Well, that's as may be,
but the law's the law and they'll have to go.

183
00:11:36,420 --> 00:11:39,253
- Another cranberry juice?
- I'm fine, thank you.

184
00:11:52,260 --> 00:11:53,488
[CLANKING]

185
00:11:57,100 --> 00:11:58,613
[CLEARS THROAT]

186
00:11:59,900 --> 00:12:02,698
I hope you're not planning on driving that.

187
00:12:02,900 --> 00:12:03,969
No.

188
00:12:13,820 --> 00:12:15,048
[CAR ENGINE STARTS]

189
00:12:19,180 --> 00:12:22,058
Right. I'm taking you to the station.

190
00:12:23,540 --> 00:12:24,859
Where is it?

191
00:12:30,180 --> 00:12:31,295
[CLEARS THROAT]

192
00:12:31,380 --> 00:12:32,449
What?

193
00:12:42,620 --> 00:12:43,735
ANGEL: Move.

194
00:12:48,140 --> 00:12:50,256
"Nicholas Angel."

195
00:12:50,860 --> 00:12:53,738
- Oh, when did you start?
- Tomorrow.

196
00:12:54,180 --> 00:12:56,489
Well, I see you've already arrested
the whole village.

197
00:12:56,580 --> 00:12:57,695
Not exactly.

198
00:12:58,500 --> 00:13:01,298
- You in for the night?
- Go on, four's free.

199
00:13:01,380 --> 00:13:04,611
- Hey, now, I need to speak to him.
- He'll be no use till the morning.

200
00:13:04,700 --> 00:13:05,815
I see.

201
00:13:05,900 --> 00:13:08,778
You really want to process all this lot?

202
00:13:09,620 --> 00:13:12,054
- My pen's running out.
- Not a problem.

203
00:13:49,460 --> 00:13:51,132
- Morning, Sergeant.
- Morning.

204
00:13:51,220 --> 00:13:52,335
Morning.

205
00:13:53,340 --> 00:13:54,455
Morning, Sergeant.

206
00:13:56,460 --> 00:13:58,257
Morning, Sergeant.

207
00:14:03,100 --> 00:14:05,216
- Lock me up.
- I'm sorry?

208
00:14:05,300 --> 00:14:07,336
I'm a slasher and I must be stopped.

209
00:14:08,180 --> 00:14:11,695
- You're a what?
- A slasher of prices.

210
00:14:13,140 --> 00:14:17,736
<i>Just kidding. I'm Simon Skinner.
I run the local supermarché.</i>

211
00:14:17,980 --> 00:14:21,290
Drop in and see me sometime.
My discounts are criminal.

212
00:14:21,660 --> 00:14:23,218
Catch me later!

213
00:14:25,140 --> 00:14:27,335
Morning, Sergeant.

214
00:14:32,620 --> 00:14:34,656
Morning, Sergeant.

215
00:14:38,140 --> 00:14:41,212
Could you tell the Inspector
I've arrived, please?

216
00:14:41,500 --> 00:14:42,774
No.

217
00:14:43,340 --> 00:14:44,534
Why?

218
00:14:44,940 --> 00:14:46,851
He's not in yet.

219
00:14:47,140 --> 00:14:49,495
- Well, how's our guest?
- Guest?

220
00:14:49,580 --> 00:14:54,017
- The inebriate in cell four.
- I don't know. Nobody tells me nothing.

221
00:14:59,260 --> 00:15:01,012
Can I get cell four open, please?

222
00:15:01,100 --> 00:15:03,091
Danny, can you open four?

223
00:15:05,540 --> 00:15:09,818
- He's gone.
- Oh, my God. Who's gone?

224
00:15:12,700 --> 00:15:16,693
- Why are you dressed like a police officer?
- Because I am one.

225
00:15:17,540 --> 00:15:19,849
Sergeant Angel, at last. Frank Butterman.

226
00:15:20,980 --> 00:15:23,938
- I see you've already met my boy.
- Yes.

227
00:15:25,820 --> 00:15:28,971
FRANK: Do forgive me.
I'm something of a Wild West nut.

228
00:15:29,060 --> 00:15:33,212
Speaking of which, that was a fair
few outlaws you rounded up last night.

229
00:15:33,380 --> 00:15:34,893
Thank you, sir.

230
00:15:34,980 --> 00:15:39,690
I admire your enthusiasm
and far be it from me to stifle your flair,

231
00:15:39,780 --> 00:15:42,374
but this isn't London.
Oh, yes, please, Danny.

232
00:15:42,460 --> 00:15:43,529
With respect, sir,

233
00:15:43,620 --> 00:15:46,737
geographical location shouldn't factor
in the application of the law.

234
00:15:46,820 --> 00:15:48,048
No, thanks.

235
00:15:48,140 --> 00:15:51,894
Statistically, Sandford is
the safest village in the country.

236
00:15:51,980 --> 00:15:54,096
But that doesn't mean
it requires anything less

