- Let's cut through here. Head him off.
- Through the gardens?

476
00:28:45,660 --> 00:28:48,174
What's the matter, Danny?
You never taken a shortcut before.

477
00:29:30,620 --> 00:29:32,292
Hey, give me that!

478
00:29:38,540 --> 00:29:40,451
"You do not have to say anything,
however it may harm your defence

479
00:29:40,540 --> 00:29:43,134
"if you fail to mention when questioned
something you later rely on in court.

480
00:29:43,220 --> 00:29:45,211
"Anything you do say
can be given in evidence."

481
00:29:45,300 --> 00:29:46,892
- Hi, Danny.
- All right, Pete?

482
00:29:46,980 --> 00:29:48,049
Do you know this man?

483
00:29:48,140 --> 00:29:49,778
Yeah, he's Auntie Jackie's
sister's brother's boy.

484
00:29:49,860 --> 00:29:51,657
And it didn't occur to you
to mention this before?

485
00:29:51,740 --> 00:29:54,459
Couldn't see his face, could I?
I'm not made of eyes.

486
00:30:04,620 --> 00:30:06,372
Impressive collar.

487
00:30:06,460 --> 00:30:08,894
Shame Mr Skinner
doesn't want to press charges.

488
00:30:08,980 --> 00:30:10,379
What do you mean,
he doesn't wanna press charges?

489
00:30:10,460 --> 00:30:14,135
I'm simply suggesting that, you know,
Peter be given a second chance

490
00:30:14,220 --> 00:30:17,053
before he becomes
just another crime statistic.

491
00:30:17,140 --> 00:30:19,859
I'm sure he's going to learn
a valuable lesson.

492
00:30:19,940 --> 00:30:23,489
- Stealing biscuits is wrong?
- Correct.

493
00:30:23,580 --> 00:30:24,615
Thanks.

494
00:30:24,700 --> 00:30:27,453
And yet we respond by not taking
a single punitive measure?

495
00:30:27,540 --> 00:30:30,373
Well, that's the way the cookie crumbles.

496
00:30:30,460 --> 00:30:32,291
Like the biscuits, isn't it?

497
00:30:32,380 --> 00:30:35,133
- Mr Skinner...
- Is everything all right?

498
00:30:35,260 --> 00:30:40,050
Well, sir, Mr Skinner feels it would
be better not to prosecute an individual

499
00:30:40,140 --> 00:30:42,131
that has committed a blatant offence.

500
00:30:42,220 --> 00:30:43,619
Leave this with me.

501
00:30:43,700 --> 00:30:46,737
I'll make sure everyone gets
their just deserts.

502
00:30:46,820 --> 00:30:48,617
<i>Oh, no!</i>

503
00:30:51,340 --> 00:30:52,773
Twenty-seven.

504
00:30:52,860 --> 00:30:56,250
<i>- DANNY: Have you ever seen Point Break?
- No.</i>

505
00:30:56,340 --> 00:30:58,570
<i>Amazing bit in Point Break
where they jump over fences.</i>

506
00:30:58,660 --> 00:31:00,491
Is there now? Twenty-nine.

507
00:31:00,580 --> 00:31:03,413
Patrick Swayze's just robbed this bank
and Keanu Reeves is chasing him

508
00:31:03,500 --> 00:31:06,298
through people's gardens,
and he goes to shoot Swayze but he can't,

509
00:31:06,380 --> 00:31:07,495
'cause he loves him so much,

510
00:31:07,580 --> 00:31:09,650
and he's firing his gun up in the air,
he's like...

511
00:31:09,740 --> 00:31:11,093
Forty.

512
00:31:11,180 --> 00:31:12,898
Have you ever fired your gun up
in the air and gone...

513
00:31:12,980 --> 00:31:16,177
No, I have not ever fired my gun
up in the air and gone...

514
00:31:16,260 --> 00:31:17,659
Thirty.

515
00:31:17,740 --> 00:31:21,289
Sorry, I... I just...
I just feel like I'm missing out sometimes.

516
00:31:21,380 --> 00:31:24,258
- I wanna do what you do.
- You do, do what I do.

517
00:31:24,340 --> 00:31:26,058
What on earth
do you think you're missing out on?

518
00:31:26,140 --> 00:31:29,450
Gun fights. Car chases.
Proper action and shit.

519
00:31:29,540 --> 00:31:32,816
Police work is not about
proper action or shit.

520
00:31:33,580 --> 00:31:34,933
Twenty-nine.

521
00:31:35,020 --> 00:31:36,294
If you had paid attention to me in school,

522
00:31:36,380 --> 00:31:39,417
you'd understand that it's not all about
gun fights and car chases.

523
00:31:40,820 --> 00:31:42,048
Fire up the roof.

524
00:31:46,500 --> 00:31:48,138
That was brilliant.

525
00:31:50,740 --> 00:31:53,129
Was I going a tad fast, Officer?

526
00:31:53,620 --> 00:31:55,611
Yes, you were, Mr Blower.

527
00:31:55,700 --> 00:31:58,817
Well, now, you see,
we are staging a homage

528
00:31:58,900 --> 00:32:02,813
<i>to William Shakespeare's Romeo and Juliet
and I'm a little late for the dress rehearsal.</i>

529
00:32:02,900 --> 00:32:05,812
I'm playing the eponymous hero, you see.

530
00:32:06,020 --> 00:32:07,612
Romeo not Juliet.

531
00:32:09,860 --> 00:32:12,499
- What are you writing?
- Everything you're saying.

532
00:32:12,580 --> 00:32:13,933
I might need to refer to it later.

533
00:32:14,020 --> 00:32:17,933
Now, Officer, I am a respected solicitor
so there's no need to...

534
00:32:18,140 --> 00:32:19,493
Just stop writing, will you?

535
00:32:19,580 --> 00:32:24,574
Look, I'm merely trying to explain
why I might have exceeded the speed limit.

536
00:32:24,660 --> 00:32:27,333
You're playing the male lead
in a homage to William Shakespeare's

537
00:32:27,420 --> 00:32:30,218
<i>Romeo and Juliet
and you're late for the dress rehearsal.</i>

538
00:32:30,300 --> 00:32:33,053
You think this is sufficient reason
to travel at 48 in a 30 zone?

539
00:32:33,140 --> 00:32:34,892
- Well, I...
- To flout speed limits

540
00:32:34,980 --> 00:32:38,859
- specifically put in place to save lives.
- Just, look, this is preposterous.

541
00:32:38,940 --> 00:32:42,569
- "Preposterous."
- Look, just stop writing!

542
00:32:42,660 --> 00:32:44,730
"Stop writing."

543
00:32:46,380 --> 00:32:50,259
Look, you're right, I apologise.

544
00:32:51,620 --> 00:32:53,850
- See what I did there?
- You hypnotised him.

545
00:32:53,940 --> 00:32:55,293
No, I used this.

546
00:32:55,380 --> 00:32:57,769
This is the most important piece
of equipment you will ever own.

547
00:32:57,860 --> 00:33:00,613
This notebook has saved my skin
more times than I care to mention.

548
00:33:00,700 --> 00:33:02,179
You should think
about using yours more often.

549
00:33:02,260 --> 00:33:04,171
- I do use mine.
- Show me.

550
00:33:09,380 --> 00:33:12,372
- That's just extraordinary.
- You should see the one on the other side.

551
00:33:18,180 --> 00:33:21,058
- What are you up to tonight?
- I have to water my Peace Lily.

552
00:33:21,140 --> 00:33:22,619
Thought you might wanna do something.

553
00:33:22,700 --> 00:33:25,692
- What exactly were you thinking?
- Don't know. Pub?

554
00:33:25,860 --> 00:33:28,897
I don't think that's a good idea. Do you?

555
00:33:31,780 --> 00:33:33,213
You two.

556
00:33:33,380 --> 00:33:37,578
<i>A Mr Blower left you tickets
for Romeo and Juliet tonight.</i>

557
00:33:37,660 --> 00:33:38,979
Said it was by way of an apology.

558
00:33:39,060 --> 00:33:40,539
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

559
00:33:40,940 --> 00:33:44,819
Well, we can't accept gifts from somebody
we've officially rebuked. So...

560
00:33:45,260 --> 00:33:46,409
Yeah.

561
00:33:47,700 --> 00:33:49,213
Nicholas. Glad I caught you.

562
00:33:49,300 --> 00:33:52,895
Wondered if you wouldn't mind
representing us at the am drams tonight.

563
00:33:52,980 --> 00:33:55,778
- Yes, sir, of course.
- And there's a spare for Danny, too.

564
00:33:55,860 --> 00:33:59,136
Yeah! Hey, come on, it might be fun.

565
00:34:05,460 --> 00:34:06,460
A dateless bargain to engrossing death.

566
00:34:06,460 --> 00:34:09,099
Here's to my love.

567
00:34:13,100 --> 00:34:14,374
[GROANING]

568
00:34:15,700 --> 00:34:16,815
Now.

569
00:34:18,860 --> 00:34:20,054
[GASPS]

570
00:34:21,420 --> 00:34:24,810
Poison? I'll kiss thy lips.

571
00:34:25,700 --> 00:34:28,658
Happily some poison
doth yet hang on them.

572
00:34:36,020 --> 00:34:37,135
Bang!

573
00:34:38,500 --> 00:34:39,899
[ALL SINGING]

574
00:34:55,220 --> 00:34:58,337
<i>Sergeant Angel, hi-hi.
Quick word for the Sandford Citizen.</i>

575
00:34:58,980 --> 00:35:00,208
It was very enjoyable.

576
00:35:00,300 --> 00:35:02,450
- "Cop Enjoys Watching Young Lovers"?
- I don't think so.

577
00:35:02,540 --> 00:35:04,098
"Local Bobby Gives Thumbs Up
To Teen Suicide"?

578
00:35:04,180 --> 00:35:05,693
That's just grossly inappropriate.

579
00:35:06,340 --> 00:35:09,616
You will try and spell his name
correctly this time, won't you, Timothy?

580
00:35:09,700 --> 00:35:12,055
Absolute tosh, wasn't it?

581
00:35:12,340 --> 00:35:16,253
And annoyingly, the understudies
are actually professional actors.

582
00:35:16,420 --> 00:35:18,775
<i>Greg over there was an extra in Straw Dogs</i>

583
00:35:18,860 --> 00:35:20,657
<i>and Sheree portrayed a cadaver
in Prime Suspect.</i>

584
00:35:20,740 --> 00:35:22,810
Sergeant Angel, you came?

585
00:35:22,900 --> 00:35:26,131
So thrilled you accepted my invitation.

586
00:35:26,220 --> 00:35:29,053
Well, our Inspector
requested we attend. So...

587
00:35:29,140 --> 00:35:33,736
Yeah, we can't accept gifts from
someone we've officially rebuked so...

588
00:35:33,820 --> 00:35:35,094
Jog on.

589
00:35:35,740 --> 00:35:38,812
Congratulations to you and to Mrs Blower.

590
00:35:40,980 --> 00:35:45,576
Oh, this is not my wife.
This is Miss Draper. My leading lady.

591
00:35:45,860 --> 00:35:50,172
Eve works in the local council, Sergeant.
Quite the lady in the know.

592
00:35:50,260 --> 00:35:53,093
- I am not.
- Nonsense.

593
00:35:53,180 --> 00:35:58,652
I'm sure if we bashed your head in, all sorts
of secrets would come tumbling out.

594
00:36:00,740 --> 00:36:04,858
Romeo, Romeo, a pint of bitter for Romeo?

595
00:36:04,940 --> 00:36:06,737
Thank you very much for coming, George.
Excuse us.

596
00:36:06,820 --> 00:36:08,856
A pleasure, my liege.

597
00:36:08,940 --> 00:36:12,216
- Eve's nice, ain't she?
- She certainly has a distinctive laugh.

598
00:36:12,300 --> 00:36:15,576
She was in my year at school.
Always had a thing for her.

599
00:36:16,340 --> 00:36:18,217
She clearly has a thing for older men.

600
00:36:19,300 --> 00:36:21,495
What, with Martin Blower? No way!

601
00:36:21,980 --> 00:36:24,540
We just sat through three hours
of so-called acting, Constable,

602
00:36:24,620 --> 00:36:27,259
their kiss was
the only convincing moment in it.

603
00:36:27,340 --> 00:36:28,932
Hey, now you come to mention it,

604
00:36:29,020 --> 00:36:31,534
I too have reason to believe
she favours the older gent.

605
00:36:31,620 --> 00:36:32,689
Really? How so?

606
00:36:32,780 --> 00:36:35,738
Marcus Carter's big brother said
he'd fingered her up the duck pond.

607
00:36:39,100 --> 00:36:40,692
Oh, Officers.

608
00:36:40,780 --> 00:36:44,250
Again let me extend
my sincere apologies for earlier.

609
00:36:44,340 --> 00:36:47,571
That's quite all right, Mr Blower. Drive safe.

610
00:36:51,340 --> 00:36:52,489
[GROANS]

611
00:36:52,580 --> 00:36:55,617
"Drive safe." Oh, my God.

612
00:36:55,700 --> 00:36:57,975
You know that's the bloke
we done for speeding earlier.

613
00:36:58,060 --> 00:37:00,858
Yeah. Hopefully,
that's the last we'll see of him.

614
00:37:11,580 --> 00:37:12,615
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

615
00:37:12,700 --> 00:37:13,974
Who is it?

616
00:37:18,380 --> 00:37:19,449
We haven't got long.

617
00:37:21,340 --> 00:37:22,489
To us.

618
00:37:22,700 --> 00:37:24,531
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

619
00:37:24,620 --> 00:37:25,814
Who is it?

620
00:37:31,620 --> 00:37:32,973
[BEEPING]

621
00:37:37,220 --> 00:37:38,494
Yeah?

622
00:37:41,260 --> 00:37:43,012
<i>...decaffeinated?
- Decaffeinated?</i>

623
00:37:47,420 --> 00:37:50,378
Little Brian Libby found them,
out on his paper round.

624
00:37:51,140 --> 00:37:53,859
Oh, he'll be having nightmares for a while.

625
00:37:54,300 --> 00:37:58,054
Must have hit the sign at some speed.
Took the whole top off.

626
00:37:58,140 --> 00:38:01,052
- I've had my top off in this lay-by.
- Tits.

627
00:38:01,140 --> 00:38:07,409
Most likely lost control,
left the road there and then ended up here.

628
00:38:09,020 --> 00:38:13,172
So, what do we reckon?

629
00:38:13,940 --> 00:38:15,339
Sergeant Angel?

630
00:38:15,900 --> 00:38:18,619
Well, we should get a proper cordon off,
screen the remains from public view.

631
00:38:18,700 --> 00:38:20,338
Close down the road
until the ambulance crew arrives,

632
00:38:20,420 --> 00:38:23,617
whereupon we should open
a single lane of traffic and ease congestion.

633
00:38:24,140 --> 00:38:25,414
Very good.

634
00:38:26,060 --> 00:38:27,095
What he said.

635
00:38:32,260 --> 00:38:34,296
- What happened, Danny?
- Car accident.

636
00:38:34,380 --> 00:38:36,052
Nasty way to go.

637
00:38:36,860 --> 00:38:38,771
Constable, official vocab guidelines state

638
00:38:38,860 --> 00:38:41,818
we no longer refer to these incidents
as "accidents," they're now "collisions."

639
00:38:41,900 --> 00:38:42,935
Right.

640
00:38:43,020 --> 00:38:48,890
"For never was there a story of more woe.
Than this of Juliet and her Romeo."

641
00:38:49,180 --> 00:38:52,695
- Excuse me?
- Martin and Eve. Such a tragedy.

642
00:38:52,780 --> 00:38:54,293
Mr Skinner, do you mind telling me

643
00:38:54,380 --> 00:38:56,496
how you know the identity
of the persons involved?

644
00:38:56,580 --> 00:38:59,890
You know how it is. News travels fast.

645
00:39:00,100 --> 00:39:04,059
<i>A love struck Romeo
sings a streetsus serenade</i>

646
00:39:04,660 --> 00:39:06,935
- What happened, Danny?
- Traffic collision.

647
00:39:08,140 --> 00:39:09,971
Hey, why can't we say "accident" again?

648
00:39:10,060 --> 00:39:12,415
Because "accident" implies
there's nobody to blame.

649
00:39:13,860 --> 00:39:15,213
Put a sock in it, town mouse.

650
00:39:15,300 --> 00:39:18,895
Yeah, you wanna be a big cop in
a small town, fuck off up the model village.

651
00:39:18,980 --> 00:39:21,289
I'm just saying,
things aren't always as simple as they look.

652
00:39:21,380 --> 00:39:23,132
Most times they are.

653
00:39:23,220 --> 00:39:25,859
Let's just wait till Doctor Hatcher
comes back with something,

654
00:39:25,940 --> 00:39:28,408
before you go jumping the Kalashnikov.

655
00:39:28,500 --> 00:39:31,492
All right, in the meantime, why don't you
check out a few of Martin Blower's clients?

656
00:39:31,580 --> 00:39:34,333
Martin Blower represents
damn near most of the village.

657
00:39:34,420 --> 00:39:35,899
Did you want us to go through
the whole phone book?

658
00:39:35,980 --> 00:39:38,653
Yeah, or put a call into Aaron A. Aaronson,
shall we?

659
00:39:38,740 --> 00:39:40,014
Please, don't be childish.

660
00:39:40,100 --> 00:39:41,328
At least consider interviewing the widow.

661
00:39:41,420 --> 00:39:43,411
Martin Blower was clearly having
an affair with Eve Draper.

662
00:39:43,500 --> 00:39:46,776
Oh, and how did you establish that?

663
00:39:46,860 --> 00:39:49,499
'Cause we sat through three hours
of so-called acting last night,

664
00:39:49,580 --> 00:39:51,889
and the kiss was
the only convincing moment in it.

665
00:39:51,980 --> 00:39:53,971
All right, pipe down, big one.

666
00:39:54,060 --> 00:39:56,494
Here, what else you got,
Crockett and Tubby?

667
00:39:56,580 --> 00:39:58,889
- Skid marks.
- Now who's being childish?

668
00:39:58,980 --> 00:40:00,732
There were no skid marks at the scene.

669
00:40:00,820 --> 00:40:03,653
Doesn't it seem a little strange that
Martin Blower would lose control of his car

670
00:40:03,740 --> 00:40:05,571
and not think to apply the brakes?

671
00:40:06,180 --> 00:40:07,408
If there were no skid marks it follows

672
00:40:07,500 --> 00:40:11,254
that for 300 yards both driver and passenger
did nothing to prevent their fate.

673
00:40:11,340 --> 00:40:13,251
You don't have to be a detective
to work that out!

674
00:40:13,340 --> 00:40:14,455
Yeah.

675
00:40:14,540 --> 00:40:17,498
- Are you causing trouble?
- Yes, they are.

676
00:40:17,580 --> 00:40:20,652
Well, a spot of bother up at Ellroy Farm.

677
00:40:20,740 --> 00:40:24,096
Old Arthur Webley's been clipping
hedgerows that don't belong to him.

678
00:40:24,180 --> 00:40:25,818
- Yes, sir?
- That's it.

679
00:40:26,780 --> 00:40:27,849
Yes, sir.

680
00:40:33,580 --> 00:40:36,777
- Why do we need the dog?
- It's not the dog we need.

681
00:40:37,820 --> 00:40:39,776
[CHATTERING INCOHERENTLY]

682
00:40:44,220 --> 00:40:45,255
Right.

683
00:40:45,340 --> 00:40:46,409
What did he say?

684
00:40:46,500 --> 00:40:48,491
[CHATTERING INCOHERENTLY]

685
00:40:52,060 --> 00:40:53,652
- What did he say?
- He said, "An 'edge is an 'edge.

686
00:40:53,740 --> 00:40:55,253
"He only chopped it down
'cause it spoilt his view.

687
00:40:55,340 --> 00:40:56,693
"What's Reaper moaning about?"

688
00:40:56,780 --> 00:40:57,815
Right.

689
00:40:57,900 --> 00:40:59,174
Look, I appreciate your position,
Mr Webley,

690
00:40:59,260 --> 00:41:02,297
but you can't go around chopping down
other people's hedges without permission.

691
00:41:04,260 --> 00:41:05,534
"Yes, I suppose."

692
00:41:05,620 --> 00:41:06,689
Thank you.

693
00:41:07,420 --> 00:41:08,853
All right.

694
00:41:10,460 --> 00:41:13,179
Mr Webley,
I trust you have a licence for that firearm?

695
00:41:15,460 --> 00:41:16,973
He does for this one.

696
00:41:18,660 --> 00:41:20,059
What do you mean by "this one"?

697
00:41:33,100 --> 00:41:35,660
By the power of Grey Skull.

698
00:41:35,740 --> 00:41:37,617
Where on earth did you get these?

699
00:41:37,700 --> 00:41:39,531
- Found them.
- He found them!

700
00:41:39,620 --> 00:41:43,056
- And what is this?
- Sea mine.

701
00:41:43,140 --> 00:41:44,619
Sea mine.

702
00:41:44,860 --> 00:41:47,294
Well, Mr Webley,
this is an extremely dangerous collection.

703
00:41:47,380 --> 00:41:48,813
It's a wonder nobody's been hurt before.

704
00:41:48,900 --> 00:41:50,811
No, it's just a lot of junk.

705
00:41:51,980 --> 00:41:53,538
[CLANKING]

706
00:42:00,660 --> 00:42:02,093
[CLICKING]

707
00:42:02,500 --> 00:42:04,491
ANGEL: Move, move, move!

708
00:42:20,420 --> 00:42:21,773
[COW MOOING]

709
00:42:24,620 --> 00:42:27,373
<i>- TURNER: You what?
- No, apparently it's been deactivated. Over.</i>

710
00:42:27,460 --> 00:42:29,451
That's right, deactivated!

711
00:42:29,540 --> 00:42:31,371
- It's not live.
- It looks live.

712
00:42:31,460 --> 00:42:32,495
<i>All right.</i>

713
00:42:54,580 --> 00:42:56,810
That was quite an impressive haul today,
