00:57:56,540 --> 00:57:58,610
Do you really think this is murder?

951
00:57:58,780 --> 00:58:00,293
I just don't think we should rule it out,
that's all.

952
00:58:00,380 --> 00:58:01,813
Yeah. I think you're right.

953
00:58:01,900 --> 00:58:04,050
I think you're talking a load of old shit.

954
00:58:04,740 --> 00:58:07,857
He thinks you're talking a load of shit.
Swings and roundabouts, isn't it?

955
00:58:08,180 --> 00:58:09,374
CARTWRIGHT: Pain in the arse.

956
00:58:09,620 --> 00:58:11,576
- Did you find anything?
- Yeah.

957
00:58:11,660 --> 00:58:13,412
I was extremely shocked
when I looked at my watch

958
00:58:13,500 --> 00:58:14,853
and discovered that I should be in the pub.

959
00:58:14,940 --> 00:58:17,135
Did you go to his house?
Did you read his articles?

960
00:58:17,220 --> 00:58:20,530
<i>If you wanna wade through every copy of
the Sandford bloody Citizen, be our guest.</i>

961
00:58:20,620 --> 00:58:22,451
It's your job, isn't it? Detect!

962
00:58:22,540 --> 00:58:26,613
This ain't the city, Mr Angel.
Not everyone's a murdering psychopath.

963
00:58:26,780 --> 00:58:30,056
It's high time you realised that.
You and your monkey.

964
00:58:33,260 --> 00:58:35,137
Did he mean me or that?

965
00:58:36,740 --> 00:58:38,856
Oh, maybe we should go home.

966
00:58:39,060 --> 00:58:42,018
- What do you mean?
- Well, there's nothing going on, is there?

967
00:58:42,100 --> 00:58:43,658
Have you listened to anything that I've said?

968
00:58:43,740 --> 00:58:44,809
What do you mean?

969
00:58:44,900 --> 00:58:46,379
Is anything I've told you
in the last two weeks

970
00:58:46,460 --> 00:58:48,416
- sunk into that thick skull of yours?
- Yeah.

971
00:58:48,500 --> 00:58:50,138
Has it? Like what?

972
00:58:50,660 --> 00:58:52,491
You said I could be
an amazing policeman-officer.

973
00:58:52,580 --> 00:58:54,889
There's always something going on, Danny.

974
00:58:54,980 --> 00:58:58,450
And you won't be an amazing police officer
until you understand that.

975
00:58:58,540 --> 00:59:00,815
Well, I remembered something else
you said and all.

976
00:59:00,900 --> 00:59:02,458
- Oh, did you now?
- Yeah.

977
00:59:02,540 --> 00:59:04,735
You don't know how to switch off!

978
00:59:37,540 --> 00:59:38,939
<i>Well, if you wanna wade through every copy</i>

979
00:59:39,020 --> 00:59:41,215
<i>of the Sandford bloody Citizen,
be our guest.</i>

980
01:00:17,300 --> 01:00:19,768
- Morning, Constable.
- All right?

981
01:00:21,060 --> 01:00:22,891
Thanks for the monkey.

982
01:00:23,700 --> 01:00:26,134
- Yours, isn't it?
- I won it for you.

983
01:00:29,620 --> 01:00:31,497
Danny, I think I'm on to something.

984
01:00:31,580 --> 01:00:32,695
- Are you?
- Yes.

985
01:00:32,780 --> 01:00:36,932
And I think with a little deliberation
we can figure out what links these deaths.

986
01:00:37,380 --> 01:00:40,656
- We?
- Come on, partner. Let's go to work.

987
01:00:41,740 --> 01:00:43,571
Oh, oh, Sergeant Angel?

988
01:00:43,660 --> 01:00:48,097
- Someone from London called for you.
- Tell them I'll call them back.

989
01:00:48,900 --> 01:00:49,969
- Tim Messenger.
- Go.

990
01:00:50,060 --> 01:00:51,812
<i>Editor and journalist
at The Sandford Citizen.</i>

991
01:00:51,900 --> 01:00:53,128
- Fondness for puns.
- Go on.

992
01:00:53,220 --> 01:00:54,289
- Terrible speller.
- Oh, yeah?

993
01:00:54,380 --> 01:00:56,257
Nevertheless had uncovered
important information about...

994
01:00:56,340 --> 01:00:58,012
- George Merchant.
- Self-made millionaire.

995
01:00:58,150 --> 01:01:00,266
Fancied himself as a property developer.

996
01:01:00,350 --> 01:01:02,989
- Said he had big plans for Sandford.
- Pissed on the floor in The Crown.

997
01:01:03,070 --> 01:01:05,140
But more importantly,
was a good friend and client of...

998
01:01:05,230 --> 01:01:06,902
- Martin Blower.
- Respected solicitor.

999
01:01:06,990 --> 01:01:09,140
- Affirmatron.
- Leading light of the local drama society.

1000
01:01:09,230 --> 01:01:10,583
- Bad actor.
- Undoubtedly.

1001
01:01:10,670 --> 01:01:12,149
- Bad driver.
- Not necessarily.

1002
01:01:12,230 --> 01:01:13,822
- Cheated on his missus.
- Most certainly.

1003
01:01:13,910 --> 01:01:15,787
- And we both know who with.
- Eve Draper.

1004
01:01:15,870 --> 01:01:18,589
- Blower's leading lady. Distinctive laugh.
- True.

1005
01:01:18,670 --> 01:01:20,023
- Favoured older men.
- Fingered.

1006
01:01:20,110 --> 01:01:21,304
- Worked at?
- Council.

1007
01:01:21,390 --> 01:01:23,984
- More specifically?
- Department of Planning and Development.

1008
01:01:24,070 --> 01:01:25,628
Where George Merchant secured permission

1009
01:01:25,710 --> 01:01:27,985
to build his dubious mansion
on Norris Avenue.

1010
01:01:28,070 --> 01:01:29,139
So...

1011
01:01:29,230 --> 01:01:33,143
Maybe they were all accidents.
People have accidents every day.

1012
01:01:33,230 --> 01:01:34,345
[MOCKING]

1013
01:01:34,430 --> 01:01:36,819
- What are you two up to?
- Nothing.

1014
01:01:36,910 --> 01:01:37,979
Well, look sharp.

1015
01:01:38,070 --> 01:01:40,709
- There's been reports of a fire in the station.
- What?

1016
01:01:40,790 --> 01:01:44,305
<i>Happy birthday to you</i>

1017
01:01:44,390 --> 01:01:48,429
<i>Happy birthday to you</i>

1018
01:01:48,510 --> 01:01:52,025
- Danny, why didn't you say something?
- We were working, weren't we?

1019
01:01:54,310 --> 01:01:57,268
- Hey, where are you going?
- Personal errand.

1020
01:01:57,950 --> 01:01:59,542
[SIREN BLARING]

1021
01:02:03,790 --> 01:02:05,143
Hello, Miss Tiller.

1022
01:02:05,230 --> 01:02:07,824
I was wondering,
do you have any Japanese Peace Lilies?

1023
01:02:07,910 --> 01:02:09,263
Of course.

1024
01:02:09,990 --> 01:02:12,345
I was just about to pop off, actually.

1025
01:02:13,150 --> 01:02:15,345
I can never find my scissors.

1026
01:02:15,590 --> 01:02:19,378
- Is this for someone special?
- Yes. Yes, it is.

1027
01:02:21,710 --> 01:02:26,147
- Are you going somewhere, Miss Tiller?
- Yes. I'm moving away.

1028
01:02:27,230 --> 01:02:30,267
And why the move,
if you don't mind me asking?

1029
01:02:30,350 --> 01:02:34,980
- Well, just between you and I...
- Yes?

1030
01:02:35,190 --> 01:02:37,988
- You know that fella who blew up?
- George Merchant.

1031
01:02:38,070 --> 01:02:41,107
Well, George Merchant, God rest him,
wanted to buy this land,

1032
01:02:41,190 --> 01:02:44,626
so he sends round his legal fella,
Martin Blower, God rest him,

1033
01:02:44,710 --> 01:02:46,746
and I thought I might take them up on it.

1034
01:02:46,830 --> 01:02:50,379
I haven't really got that much family
round here, save for Cousin Sissy.

1035
01:02:50,470 --> 01:02:53,780
So I thought I might take them up
on the offer and move to Buford Abbey.

1036
01:02:53,870 --> 01:02:55,781
Would you like a card with this?

1037
01:02:55,950 --> 01:02:58,145
No, sorry, you were talking about the offer?

1038
01:02:58,230 --> 01:03:01,302
Well, it turns out that Martin Blower,
God rest him,

1039
01:03:01,390 --> 01:03:03,460
knew where the new bypass road is going

1040
01:03:03,550 --> 01:03:06,508
because he was knocking off Eve Draper
from the council, God rest her,

1041
01:03:06,590 --> 01:03:10,139
and then that reporter, God rest him,
finds out about the route

1042
01:03:10,230 --> 01:03:12,266
and tells me this land's very valuable.

1043
01:03:12,350 --> 01:03:16,263
Ten times what George Merchant and
Martin Blower, God rest them, offered me.

1044
01:03:16,350 --> 01:03:19,228
So, with them having passed on,
I decided to sell it on myself

1045
01:03:19,310 --> 01:03:21,983
to some folks from the city
that Martin, George and Eve,

1046
01:03:22,070 --> 01:03:24,026
God rest the lot of them,
had been talking to.

1047
01:03:24,110 --> 01:03:26,829
Apparently, they want to build
a big shopping centre or something.

1048
01:03:26,910 --> 01:03:29,583
Of course, Cousin Sissy won't be
too happy about that,

1049
01:03:29,670 --> 01:03:31,661
but as far as I'm concerned,
Cousin Sissy can go and fuck...

1050
01:03:31,750 --> 01:03:34,264
Would you just excuse me,
for just one second?

1051
01:03:48,870 --> 01:03:50,019
Stop!

1052
01:03:50,870 --> 01:03:52,428
In the name of the law!

1053
01:04:48,230 --> 01:04:50,141
<i>Hang about, hang about.</i>

1054
01:04:50,950 --> 01:04:53,145
You're saying this wasn't an accident?

1055
01:04:54,430 --> 01:04:56,386
Leslie Tiller was fucking murdered!

1056
01:04:56,470 --> 01:04:57,869
- What, just like Tim Messenger?
- Yes!

1057
01:04:57,950 --> 01:04:59,065
- And George Merchant?
- Yes!

1058
01:04:59,150 --> 01:05:00,344
- And Eve Draper?
- Yes!

1059
01:05:00,430 --> 01:05:01,988
- And Martin Blower?
- No, actually.

1060
01:05:02,070 --> 01:05:03,867
- Really?
- 'Course he fucking was!

1061
01:05:03,950 --> 01:05:05,781
Thank you, Danny.

1062
01:05:05,870 --> 01:05:09,067
Oh, murder, murder, murder.
Change the fucking record.

1063
01:05:09,630 --> 01:05:10,745
Thank you, Andy.

1064
01:05:10,830 --> 01:05:14,903
Come on, Sergeant, you've gotta accept
it was just another nasty accident.

1065
01:05:14,990 --> 01:05:16,025
What are you suggesting?

1066
01:05:16,110 --> 01:05:18,499
That Leslie Tiller tripped
and fell on her own shears?

1067
01:05:18,590 --> 01:05:20,945
Ben Fletcher fell
on his pitchfork the other week.

1068
01:05:21,030 --> 01:05:24,340
Yeah, accidents happen all the time.
What makes you think it was murder?

1069
01:05:24,430 --> 01:05:27,263
- Because I was there!
- There's a point.

1070
01:05:27,350 --> 01:05:28,669
Why were you there?

1071
01:05:28,750 --> 01:05:32,823
I was buying Constable Butterman
a Japanese Peace Lily for his birthday.

1072
01:05:32,910 --> 01:05:35,378
What absolute horseshit.

1073
01:05:35,470 --> 01:05:39,258
I chased a suspect from the scene.
Innocent people don't run!

1074
01:05:39,350 --> 01:05:42,308
Here, maybe it was our old friend,
the cactus thief.

1075
01:05:42,390 --> 01:05:44,984
Oh, yeah, he was a prickly customer,
weren't he?

1076
01:05:45,790 --> 01:05:48,384
Am I going completely mad?

1077
01:05:50,430 --> 01:05:52,022
Maybe you are.

1078
01:05:53,870 --> 01:05:56,509
Maybe you did it.

1079
01:05:56,590 --> 01:05:59,787
Yeah, seeing as how you're such
a big fan of murder.

1080
01:05:59,870 --> 01:06:01,223
- What the...
- Sergeant Angel?

1081
01:06:01,310 --> 01:06:03,699
Yes! Sir.

1082
01:06:06,190 --> 01:06:08,943
Nicholas, Nicholas, Nicholas.

1083
01:06:09,030 --> 01:06:11,498
What am I going to do with you?

1084
01:06:11,590 --> 01:06:15,947
- Sir, you have to understand...
- No, you have to understand.

1085
01:06:16,910 --> 01:06:20,698
The boys here aren't used
to the concepts you're bandying about.

1086
01:06:21,310 --> 01:06:23,699
The "M" word, Nicholas.

1087
01:06:23,790 --> 01:06:27,829
There hasn't been a recorded murder
in Sandford for 20 years.

1088
01:06:27,910 --> 01:06:29,662
But, sir, I'm certain.

1089
01:06:30,150 --> 01:06:33,267
And what's more, I know who did it.

1090
01:06:39,070 --> 01:06:40,901
Can I see the manager, please?

1091
01:06:46,190 --> 01:06:51,901
<i>Mr Skinner to the Manager's office.
Manager's office. Mr Skinner.</i>

1092
01:06:52,590 --> 01:06:55,900
Sergeant Angel.
And to what do I owe this pleasure?

1093
01:06:55,990 --> 01:06:59,903
Simon Skinner, I'm arresting you
on suspicion of the murder of Leslie Tiller.

1094
01:06:59,990 --> 01:07:03,300
Leslie Tiller's dead? How?

1095
01:07:03,430 --> 01:07:05,660
She tripped and fell on her own shears.

1096
01:07:05,750 --> 01:07:06,819
[GROANS]

1097
01:07:07,230 --> 01:07:10,427
I'm also arresting you on suspicion of
the murder of Tim Messenger on May 1st,

1098
01:07:10,510 --> 01:07:12,068
of George Merchant on April 29th

1099
01:07:12,150 --> 01:07:14,618
and of Eve Draper
and Martin Blower on April 28th.

1100
01:07:14,710 --> 01:07:18,544
- Why on earth would I do that, Sergeant?
- I'm glad you asked.

1101
01:07:20,230 --> 01:07:22,300
My suspicions were first aroused
when you appeared

1102
01:07:22,390 --> 01:07:25,063
<i>at the scene of the Blower-Draper death,
on the outskirts of Sandford,</i>

1103
01:07:25,150 --> 01:07:28,825
<i>despite the fact you live and work
in the centre of the village.</i>

1104
01:07:29,990 --> 01:07:34,142
I couldn't help but recall your comments
at the theatre on the previous evening.

1105
01:07:34,390 --> 01:07:37,223
<i>When you not only indicated
an awareness of the couple's affair</i>

1106
01:07:37,310 --> 01:07:39,221
<i>but also inferred
that Eve's connections at the council</i>

1107
01:07:39,310 --> 01:07:42,143
<i>might make her privy
to important information.</i>

1108
01:07:42,230 --> 01:07:44,425
<i>You even spoke of "bashing her head in."</i>

1109
01:07:44,510 --> 01:07:47,980
Perhaps hoping you might discover
the route of the proposed Sandford Bypass.

1110
01:07:48,070 --> 01:07:50,220
<i>You were already suspicious
that George Merchant was buying up</i>

1111
01:07:50,310 --> 01:07:52,505
a large area of land
on the outskirts of Sandford,

1112
01:07:52,590 --> 01:07:55,423
<i>after an article Tim Messenger
wrote in the Sandford Citizen.</i>

1113
01:07:55,510 --> 01:07:59,025
You see, the land Merchant was buying
had little value in of itself but,

1114
01:07:59,110 --> 01:08:02,864
<i>if it became accessible by road,
it would be a prime location for say,</i>

1115
01:08:03,230 --> 01:08:04,822
a retail park.

1116
01:08:04,910 --> 01:08:06,821
Consumed with concern for your business

1117
01:08:06,910 --> 01:08:08,866
and potential disloyalty
from fickle customers,

1118
01:08:08,950 --> 01:08:11,418
you yourself expressed a wish to behead.

1119
01:08:11,910 --> 01:08:14,470
<i>You killed the competition in cold blood.</i>

1120
01:08:14,550 --> 01:08:16,381
<i>Staging the murders as accidents.</i>

1121
01:08:16,470 --> 01:08:19,428
<i>You used a vehicle removal truck
to stage the Blower-Draper death</i>

1122
01:08:19,510 --> 01:08:21,341
<i>and incinerated an old man
in his own house.</i>

1123
01:08:21,430 --> 01:08:24,502
<i>Covering your tracks with the judicial
application of bacon and beans.</i>

1124
01:08:24,590 --> 01:08:27,423
However, there was a loose end.

1125
01:08:28,430 --> 01:08:29,829
Tim Messenger.

1126
01:08:29,910 --> 01:08:31,980
<i>Splattered before he could share with me</i>

1127
01:08:32,070 --> 01:08:34,903
<i>what he told Leslie Tiller
that very afternoon.</i>

1128
01:08:34,990 --> 01:08:37,709
<i>The true value of her land.</i>

1129
01:08:38,070 --> 01:08:40,868
Upon discovering she was about
to sell up to the developers,

1130
01:08:40,950 --> 01:08:43,669
you brutally murdered her
with her own shears.

1131
01:08:43,750 --> 01:08:48,301
And made good your escape utilising
your impressive skills as a fun runner.

1132
01:08:54,510 --> 01:08:58,139
Very entertaining. But I rather think
you've been watching too many films.

1133
01:08:58,230 --> 01:08:59,583
[CLEARS THROAT]

1134
01:08:59,670 --> 01:09:00,705
He hasn't.

1135
01:09:00,790 --> 01:09:04,385
Why would I kill Leslie?
You clearly aren't aware that we're related.

1136
01:09:04,470 --> 01:09:06,938
Oh, but I am, "Cousin Sissy."

1137
01:09:08,390 --> 01:09:12,542
I'm afraid my nickname of Sissy
is only a revelation to yourself.

1138
01:09:12,830 --> 01:09:16,061
My teenage years studying ballet
are well known.

1139
01:09:16,150 --> 01:09:19,187
- Yeah, Sissy Skinner.
- What a Gaylord.

1140
01:09:19,270 --> 01:09:20,749
Thank you, Andrews.

1141
01:09:20,830 --> 01:09:24,061
Now, despite my comments
about "beheading" customers,

1142
01:09:24,150 --> 01:09:27,540
I personally relish the competition
of another store.

1143
01:09:27,630 --> 01:09:31,100
Anything to energise my workforce.

1144
01:09:32,550 --> 01:09:36,987
And anyway, what makes you think
I could dislodge part of the church roof?

1145
01:09:37,070 --> 01:09:39,425
Or for that matter, stage a car crash?

1146
01:09:39,510 --> 01:09:42,741
It's a well known fact that
the church roof is in dire need of repair.

1147
01:09:42,830 --> 01:09:44,900
And isn't it true
that two of your own employees

1148
01:09:44,990 --> 01:09:47,345
operate the vehicle removal service
for the council?

1149
01:09:47,430 --> 01:09:49,705
Sergeant, this is the 21st Century.

1150
01:09:49,790 --> 01:09:52,588
Many people hold down several jobs.

1151
01:09:52,670 --> 01:09:56,219
I myself host a life drawing class
at the Village Hall.

1152
01:09:56,310 --> 01:09:59,222
Tina here is a table dancer at Flappers.

1153
01:09:59,550 --> 01:10:03,259
Nevertheless, you could have utilised
the vehicle removal truck for your own ends.

1154
01:10:03,350 --> 01:10:05,306
These accusations
are quite meaningless, Sergeant,

1155
01:10:05,390 --> 01:10:07,904
unless you can back them up
with hard evidence.

1156
01:10:07,990 --> 01:10:10,458
Well, you've got me there.

1157
01:10:10,550 --> 01:10:12,461
I'd need something conclusive.

1158
01:10:12,550 --> 01:10:14,620
Something that placed you
at the scene of the crime.

1159
01:10:14,710 --> 01:10:18,589
Perhaps a wound you sustained on
a piece of broken glass this very evening.

1160
01:10:20,150 --> 01:10:21,742
This very evening.

1161
01:10:22,950 --> 01:10:26,101
Sergeant, this is beginning
to get embarrassing.

1162
01:10:26,190 --> 01:10:29,227
How could I possibly be
in several places at once?

1163
01:10:31,430 --> 01:10:35,901
I'm sure the store's security footage
will absolve me.

1164
01:10:36,590 --> 01:10:39,150
Do feel free to spool through.

1165
01:10:55,910 --> 01:10:56,945
I can handle this, Danny.

1166
01:10:57,030 --> 01:11:00,181
You might as well go back
and just enjoy the rest of your birthday.

1167
01:11:00,270 --> 01:11:02,738
- Did you really get me that plant?
- Yes, I did.

1168
01:11:02,830 --> 01:11:06,140
But it's been impounded as evidence.

1169
01:11:06,230 --> 01:11:10,667
Well, I mean,
maybe Dad will still let me water it, eh?

1170
01:11:10,750 --> 01:11:11,865
Yeah.

1171
01:11:15,150 --> 01:11:16,503
Sergeant, I wanted you to know that

1172
01:11:16,590 --> 01:11:19,787
if I do indeed now
own the land belonging to...

1173
01:11:21,470 --> 01:11:27,067
belonging to Leslie, that I intend to turn it
into a memorial garden, in her honour.

1174
01:11:27,150 --> 01:11:31,541
Mr Skinner, what you do with your land
is of no concern of mine,

1175
01:11:32,630 --> 01:11:34,143
[BLOWS RASPBERRY]

1176
01:11:34,230 --> 01:11:35,379
So jog on.

1177
01:11:36,230 --> 01:11:40,667
Michael, will you escort the Sergeant
off the premises when he's quite finished?

1178
01:11:40,750 --> 01:11:42,229
Yarp.

1179
01:11:45,230 --> 01:11:49,382
I just can't believe Leslie's dead.
How did it happen?

1180
01:11:49,470 --> 01:11:51,700
She tripped and fell on her own shears.

1181
01:11:59,510 --> 01:12:01,626
Hey, that weren't me.

1182
01:12:09,350 --> 01:12:10,465
Hey, look.

1183
01:12:10,550 --> 01:12:13,144
Look, Mr Treacher's
got his big coat on again.

1184
01:12:16,670 --> 01:12:20,902
- You want anything from the shop?
- Cornetto.

1185
01:12:23,350 --> 01:12:27,389
- No luck catching them killers, then?
- It's just the one killer, actually.

1186
01:12:30,630 --> 01:12:33,781
<i>- No luck catching them killers, then?
- It's just the one killer, actually.</i>

1187
01:12:33,870 --> 01:12:37,067
<i>- No luck catching them killers, then?
- It's just the one killer, actually.</i>

1188
01:12:37,150 --> 01:12:40,984
<i>- No luck catching them killers, then?
- It's just the one killer, actually.</i>

1189
01:12:41,070 --> 01:12:44,187
- What's the matter? You got brain-freeze?
- No, I got brainwave.

1190
01:12:44,270 --> 01:12:46,465
Get us back to the station, now!

1191
01:12:47,150 --> 01:12:48,424
[EXCLAIMS]

1192
01:12:53,150 --> 01:12:54,788
- It's more than one person.
- Come again?

1193
01:12:54,870 --> 01:12:57,623
- It's more than one killer.
- It was Skinner a minute ago.

1194
01:12:57,710 --> 01:12:58,745
Yeah, well, maybe it still is.

1195
01:12:58,830 --> 01:13:01,105
You know, maybe he's... Maybe he's
not alone. Maybe there are others.

1196
01:13:01,190 --> 01:13:06,139
Nicholas, you're an exceptional officer.
But I've seen this before.

1197
01:13:06,590 --> 01:13:09,058
- Sir?
- Sergeant Popwell.

1198
01:13:09,150 --> 01:13:11,869
It was exactly the same thing.

1199
01:13:11,950 --> 01:13:16,182
You've come from a city
where there's danger round every corner,

1200
01:13:16,630 --> 01:13:19,064
and it's driven you round the bend.

1201
01:13:19,550 --> 01:13:20,778
Yes, sir.

1202
01:13:21,030 --> 01:13:24,340
Do yourself a favour. Sleep on it.

1203
01:13:24,430 --> 01:13:29,948
And if you still feel the same in the morning,
I give you my word, I'll get right on to it.

1204
01:13:34,110 --> 01:13:36,908
Hey. Hey, what's happening?
What's going on?

1205
01:13:37,510 --> 01:13:41,298
Nothing, nothing.
I'm just gonna go back to the hotel.

1206
01:13:41,390 --> 01:13:46,669
- I mean, do you want a lift?
- No, no, I could do with a walk.

1207
01:14:44,630 --> 01:14:46,382
<i>[LULLABY MUSIC PLAYING]</i>

1208
01:14:47,510 --> 01:14:50,308
Hey, big one, playtime's over.

1209
01:14:54,510 --> 01:14:55,829
<i>SKINNER ON WALKIE-TALKIE: Michael?</i>

1210
01:14:56,670 --> 01:14:59,230
<i>Michael? Are you there?</i>

1211
01:14:59,870 --> 01:15:03,749
<i>Michael? Is everything okay?</i>

1212
01:15:06,310 --> 01:15:07,425
Yarp.

1213
01:15:07,510 --> 01:15:10,149
<i>Sergeant Angel's been taken care of?</i>

1214
01:15:10,230 --> 01:15:11,299
Yarp.

1215
01:15:11,390 --> 01:15:13,745
<i>He's not gonna get back up again?</i>

1216
01:15:16,270 --> 01:15:17,498
Narp!

1217
01:15:18,710 --> 01:15:21,178
<i>Good. Proceed to the castle.</i>

1218
01:15:26,190 --> 01:15:27,862
Frank, this shit just got real.

1219
01:15:27,950 --> 01:15:31,579
Skinner just sent someone to kill me,
and, now, now he's gone somewhere.

1220
01:15:31,670 --> 01:15:34,138
Up to the... To the castle, I think.
I'm gonna... I'm gonna go after him.

1221
01:15:34,230 --> 01:15:36,460
Okay? It's Nicholas, by the way.

1222
01:15:38,470 --> 01:15:42,782
Oh, my God.
What happened to your Peace Lily?

1223
01:15:43,030 --> 01:15:46,784
Danny. Danny, just stay here, okay?
And watch him, and call your dad.

1224
01:15:46,870 --> 01:15:48,861
- Tell him I was right.
- What are you gonna do?

1225
01:15:48,950 --> 01:15:53,387
- I'm gonna bust this thing wide open.
- Nicholas, wait.

1226
01:15:53,470 --> 01:15:57,065
- You might need this.
- Thanks, partner.

1227
01:16:12,630 --> 01:16:14,222
[CHANTING]

1228
01:16:28,910 --> 01:16:32,186
<i>SKINNER: How could I possibly be
in several places at once?</i>

1229
01:16:32,270 --> 01:16:35,307
<i>How could I possibly be
in several places at once?</i>

1230
01:16:35,390 --> 01:16:38,541
<i>How could I possibly be
in several places at once?</i>

1231
01:16:39,630 --> 01:16:43,589
<i>JOYCE: I just can't believe Leslie's dead.
How did it happen?</i>

1232
01:16:43,670 --> 01:16:46,628
<i>WEAVER: You'll find that we run
a very tight ship here.</i>

1233
01:16:46,710 --> 01:16:48,462
<i>REVEREND SHOO TER:
Who could do something like this?</i>

1234
01:16:48,550 --> 01:16:51,781
<i>HATCHER: Seems like Mr Merchant tried
to have a little fry up and left the gas on.</i>

1235
01:16:51,870 --> 01:16:53,144
<i>HATCHER: Nasty way to go.</i>

1236
01:16:53,230 --> 01:16:54,299
<i>AMANDA: What happened, Danny?</i>

1237
01:16:54,390 --> 01:16:56,142
<i>ANNETTE:
No luck catching them killers, then?</i>

1238
01:16:56,230 --> 01:16:58,027
<i>No luck catching them killers, then?</i>

1239
01:16:58,110 --> 01:17:00,226
<i>No luck catching them...</i>

1240
01:17:03,550 --> 01:17:05,859
Now, quick announcement before we begin.

1241
01:17:05,950 --> 01:17:10,148
Janet Barker has decided
to call her boys Roger and Martin.

1242
01:17:10,230 --> 01:17:15,304
And the christening will be
a week on Saturday and we're all invited.

1243
01:17:15,550 --> 01:17:17,780
- Tom.
- Thanks, Joyce.

1244
01:17:17,990 --> 01:17:20,982
Now, you'll all be delighted to hear

1245
01:17:21,070 --> 01:17:25,541
that the tenacious Sergeant Angel
has been taken care of.

1246
01:17:25,630 --> 01:17:30,988
Joyce will discover the Sergeant lying
on the wet floor of his bathroom,

1247
01:17:31,070 --> 01:17:35,143
having slipped
and tragically broken his neck.

1248
01:17:35,230 --> 01:17:37,221
So, with the dispatch of the Sergeant,

1249
01:17:37,310 --> 01:17:41,223
we will now be able to concentrate
on the eradication of our hoodie infestation.

1250
01:17:41,310 --> 01:17:42,345
Quite right.

1251
01:17:42,430 --> 01:17:45,740
After which, nothing will stand in our way.

1252
01:17:45,830 --> 01:17:48,583
Oh, I beg to differ, Mr Weaver.

1253
01:17:48,670 --> 01:17:52,743
Well, well, well, I see we have visitors.

1254
01:17:53,070 --> 01:17:56,107
Sergeant Nicholas Angel.
Sandford Police Service.

1255
01:17:56,190 --> 01:17:58,829
My, he is tenacious, isn't he?

1256
01:17:58,910 --> 01:18:01,663
I'm arresting you under suspicion
of conspiracy to commit murder.

1257
01:18:01,750 --> 01:18:04,423
Oh, come, come, Sergeant.

1258
01:18:04,510 --> 01:18:06,023
You should be ashamed.

1259
01:18:06,110 --> 01:18:09,546
- Calling yourself a community that cares.
- Oh, but we do care, Nicholas.

1260
01:18:09,630 --> 01:18:11,302
It's all about the greater good.

1261
01:18:11,390 --> 01:18:12,823
ALL: The greater good.

1262
01:18:12,910 --> 01:18:14,343
How can this be for the greater good?

1263
01:18:14,430 --> 01:18:15,909
ALL: The greater good.

1264
01:18:15,990 --> 01:18:18,026
You see, as much as I enjoyed
your wild theories, Sergeant,

1265
01:18:18,110 --> 01:18:19,748
the truth is far less complex.

1266
01:18:19,830 --> 01:18:24,824
Blower's fate was simply the result
of his being an appalling actor.

1267
01:18:26,270 --> 01:18:27,464
ALL: Quite appalling.

1268
01:18:27,550 --> 01:18:29,222
You murdered him for that?

1269
01:18:30,270 --> 01:18:32,579
- Well, he murdered Bill Shakespeare.
- What?

1270
01:18:32,670 --> 01:18:36,026
The Dramatic Society
is an important feather in our cap.

1271
01:18:36,350 --> 01:18:37,749
<i>HATCHER: Couldn't let
Blower jeopardise that.</i>

1272
01:18:37,830 --> 01:18:39,980
Not when we had two semi-professionals
waiting in the wings.

1273
01:18:40,070 --> 01:18:42,538
<i>Let's not forget that Greg
was an extra in Straw Dogs.</i>

1274
01:18:42,630 --> 01:18:44,427
<i>And Sheree played a cadaver
in Prime Suspect.</i>

1275
01:18:44,510 --> 01:18:45,863
Yes, I know!

1276
01:18:45,950 --> 01:18:48,464
Martin was less concerned
with the reputation of the village

1277
01:18:48,550 --> 01:18:51,622
than he was with his sordid affair
with Eve Draper.

1278
01:18:51,710 --> 01:18:53,223
And so Eve deserved to die too?

1279
01:18:53,310 --> 01:18:55,619
Well, she did have a very annoying laugh.

1280
01:18:55,710 --> 01:18:56,904
ALL: Annoying.

1281
01:18:56,990 --> 01:18:59,709
- And, and George Merchant?
- He had an awful house.

1282
01:18:59,990 --> 01:19:01,025
ALL: Awful.

1283
01:19:01,110 --> 01:19:02,702
We begged him in vain
to make his residence

1284
01:19:02,790 --> 01:19:05,224
more in keeping
with the village's rustic aesthetic.

1285
01:19:06,270 --> 01:19:08,738
And what about Tim Messenger?
What was his crime?

1286
01:19:08,830 --> 01:19:13,346
<i>Tim Messenger's tenure as editor of
the Sandford Citizen has been unbearable.</i>

1287
01:19:13,430 --> 01:19:17,105
Our once great paper had
become riddled with tabloid journalism.

1288
01:19:17,190 --> 01:19:19,067
<i>Not to mention persistent errors.</i>

1289
01:19:19,150 --> 01:19:22,267
- He listed her age as 55.
- When, actually, I'm 53.

1290
01:19:22,350 --> 01:19:23,783
Fifty-three.

1291
01:19:23,870 --> 01:19:25,462
What, what about Leslie Tiller?
One of your own?

1292
01:19:25,550 --> 01:19:27,939
Her horticultural expertise helped
put Sandford on the map.

1293
01:19:28,030 --> 01:19:29,986
Oh, she was ever so good.

1294
01:19:30,070 --> 01:19:32,140
Cousin Leslie was a terrible shame.

1295
01:19:32,430 --> 01:19:35,979
But it seemed she was set on moving away.

1296
01:19:36,070 --> 01:19:39,301
We couldn't have her sharing
her green fingers with anybody else.

1297
01:19:39,390 --> 01:19:41,267
Not least those heathens at Buford Abbey.

1298
01:19:41,350 --> 01:19:43,910
If we can't have her, no one can.

1299
01:19:43,990 --> 01:19:45,503
How can this be for the greater good?

1300
01:19:45,590 --> 01:19:47,546
- ALL: The greater good.
- Shut it!

1301
01:19:47,630 --> 01:19:50,667
These people died for no reason.
No reason whatsoever!

1302
01:19:50,750 --> 01:19:53,139
Oh, I wouldn't say that.

1303
01:19:54,830 --> 01:19:56,149
Hello, Nicholas.

1304
01:19:57,190 --> 01:19:59,021
I was like you once.

1305
01:19:59,630 --> 01:20:02,906
I believed in the immutable word of the law.

1306
01:20:03,190 --> 01:20:06,865
That is until the night Mrs Butterman
was taken from me.

1307
01:20:07,750 --> 01:20:10,310
You see,
no one loved Sandford more than her.

1308
01:20:10,390 --> 01:20:14,224
She was head of the Women's Institute,
chair of the floral committee.

1309
01:20:14,310 --> 01:20:16,301
When they started
the Village of the Year contest,

1310
01:20:16,390 --> 01:20:19,939
she worked round the clock.
I've never seen such dedication.

1311
01:20:21,230 --> 01:20:26,350
On the eve of the adjudicator's arrival,
some travellers moved into Callahan Park.

1312
01:20:27,110 --> 01:20:30,500
Before you could say, "Gypsy scum,"
we were knee-deep in dog muck,

1313
01:20:30,590 --> 01:20:32,820
thieving kids and crusty jugglers.

1314
01:20:32,910 --> 01:20:34,582
ALL: Crusty jugglers.

1315
01:20:34,670 --> 01:20:37,628
We lost the title and Irene lost her mind.

1316
01:20:38,550 --> 01:20:42,543
She drove her Datsun Cherry
into Sandford Gorge.

1317
01:20:42,630 --> 01:20:47,545
From that moment on,
I swore that I would do her proud.

1318
01:20:47,870 --> 01:20:52,182
And whatever the cost,
we would make Sandford great again.

1319
01:20:52,510 --> 01:20:54,307
Sir, this doesn't make any sense.

1320
01:20:54,390 --> 01:20:58,099
The adjudicators arrive tomorrow.
We had to get everything ready.

1321
01:20:58,190 --> 01:21:00,784
Are you saying this is all about
winning the Best Village Award?

1322
01:21:00,870 --> 01:21:04,419
This is the best village, Nicholas.
You've seen the people.

1323
01:21:04,510 --> 01:21:08,788
- They're happy, contented.
- They're living in a dream world.

1324
01:21:08,870 --> 01:21:11,384
Sergeant Popwell
thought much the same as you.

1325
01:21:11,470 --> 01:21:13,426
I'm disappointed
you can't see the bigger picture.

1326
01:21:13,510 --> 01:21:15,819
Well, I'm happy to disappoint you, sir.

1327
01:21:15,910 --> 01:21:17,582
And I'm afraid
you're gonna have to come with me.

1328
01:21:17,670 --> 01:21:19,661
You are all gonna have to come with me.

1329
01:21:19,750 --> 01:21:23,663
No, Nicholas, I'm afraid it is you

1330
01:21:23,750 --> 01:21:26,389
who is going to have to come with us.

1331
01:21:34,070 --> 01:21:35,628
Danny, no.

1332
01:21:39,830 --> 01:21:41,263
Back off! Back off!

1333
01:21:41,350 --> 01:21:43,500
Or I swear to God,
you'll be explaining how Danny tripped over

1334
01:21:43,590 --> 01:21:44,989
and accidentally cut off his own head.

1335
01:21:45,070 --> 01:21:47,140
Come on, Nicholas.
You haven't got it in you.

1336
01:21:47,230 --> 01:21:48,504
I mean it!

1337
01:21:52,030 --> 01:21:53,224
Shit!

1338
01:22:07,390 --> 01:22:10,587
<i>FRANK: [ECHOING]
Gypsy scum. Travellers.</i>

1339
01:22:10,670 --> 01:22:13,628
<i>Thieving kids. Dog muck.</i>

1340
01:22:15,790 --> 01:22:17,587
<i>Crusty jugglers.</i>

1341
01:22:17,790 --> 01:22:21,226
<i>Crusty jugglers. Crusty jugglers.</i>

1342
01:22:22,070 --> 01:22:23,344
<i>Crusty jugglers.</i>

1343
01:22:23,430 --> 01:22:26,900
<i>There hasn't been a recorded murder
in Sandford for 20 years.</i>

1344
01:22:26,990 --> 01:22:29,823
<i>There's a reason we accommodate
a few of the younglings at the pub.</i>

1345
01:22:29,910 --> 01:22:32,344
<i>Spot of bother up at Ellroy Farm.</i>

1346
01:22:32,430 --> 01:22:35,103
<i>I'll make sure everyone gets
their just deserts.</i>

1347
01:22:36,070 --> 01:22:37,901
<i>[VOICES ECHOING]</i>

1348
01:22:40,030 --> 01:22:42,783
<i>WEAVER: If we don't come down hard
on these clowns...</i>

1349
01:22:42,870 --> 01:22:44,508
<i>FRANK: We'll get round to it.</i>

1350
01:22:56,270 --> 01:22:57,385
Danny!

1351
01:23:30,910 --> 01:23:32,184
Ta-da.

1352
01:23:32,390 --> 01:23:35,462
- [WHISPERING] What are you doing?
- Saving your skin.

1353
01:23:37,630 --> 01:23:40,224
- This is murder!
- It's not, it's ketchup.

1354
01:23:40,310 --> 01:23:42,949
I'm not talking about that,
I'm talking about the others.

1355
01:23:43,030 --> 01:23:45,863
- What others?
- The others the NWA have murdered.

1356
01:23:45,950 --> 01:23:47,224
- That's not true.
- It is!

1357
01:23:47,310 --> 01:23:49,380
Dad just said it was his special club, he...

1358
01:23:49,470 --> 01:23:51,267
I thought it was about
rapping people on the knuckles

1359
01:23:51,350 --> 01:23:54,422
- and sending them on their way.
- There are skeletons back there!

1360
01:23:54,510 --> 01:23:56,023
I don't know nothing about no skelingtons.

1361
01:23:56,110 --> 01:23:58,260
- What did you think was happening?
- Not this!

1362
01:23:58,350 --> 01:23:59,419
It's Frank.

1363
01:23:59,510 --> 01:24:01,626
He's appointed himself judge,
jury and executioner.

1364
01:24:01,710 --> 01:24:04,907
- He's not Judge Judy and executioner.
- He is!

1365
01:24:04,990 --> 01:24:08,027
- You've gotta help me take him down.
- I can't.

1366
01:24:09,030 --> 01:24:11,749
He's my dad. Take my car.

1367
01:24:12,790 --> 01:24:15,623
Go back to London.
There's nothing you can do.

1368
01:24:15,710 --> 01:24:17,143
I can come back.

1369
01:24:17,230 --> 01:24:19,266
I can come back,
and I can bring the blue fury

1370
01:24:19,350 --> 01:24:21,306
of the Metropolitan Police Service with me.

1371
01:24:21,390 --> 01:24:24,268
They'll make it disappear.
Who are they gonna believe?

1372
01:24:24,350 --> 01:24:26,989
My dad, or a loony London police officer.

1373
01:24:27,070 --> 01:24:28,549
But it won't be just me, will it?

1374
01:24:28,630 --> 01:24:31,702
We can do it together.
You and me. Partners.

1375
01:24:31,950 --> 01:24:35,545
Forget it, Nicholas. It's Sandford.

1376
01:25:25,510 --> 01:25:26,829
Is that everything? Sir?

1377
01:25:33,070 --> 01:25:36,346
Sir? Sir?

1378
01:25:37,790 --> 01:25:41,829
- Is there anything I can do for you?
- No.

1379
01:25:44,910 --> 01:25:47,105
This is something I have to do myself.

1380
01:26:11,750 --> 01:26:15,425
Another beautiful day in God's country.

1381
01:26:22,790 --> 01:26:24,223
Danny?

1382
01:26:32,910 --> 01:26:34,138
It's...

1383
01:26:39,230 --> 01:26:40,299
Mum!

1384
01:26:51,230 --> 01:26:52,629
What you gonna do?

1385
01:26:52,710 --> 01:26:55,668
Just walk in and arrest the whole village?

1386
01:26:57,350 --> 01:26:58,499
Not exactly.

1387
01:27:30,150 --> 01:27:33,267
Oh, Sergeant Angel?
Someone from London called for you.

1388
01:27:41,030 --> 01:27:43,225
I'll tell them you'll ring them back.

1389
01:27:45,390 --> 01:27:47,460
- Well, that's funny.
- What's that?

1390
01:27:47,910 --> 01:27:50,470
I didn't know we had a mounted division.

1391
01:27:50,550 --> 01:27:52,222
Nobody tells me nothing.

1392
01:28:07,950 --> 01:28:09,668
Wanna do something useful?

1393
01:28:18,750 --> 01:28:23,460
<i>AMANDA: Annette, that Sergeant Angel's
back. Check out his horse.</i>

1394
01:28:24,390 --> 01:28:26,267
<i>ANNETTE: [WHISPERS] Roger that!</i>

1395
01:28:27,910 --> 01:28:30,788
- It's...
- Angel.

1396
01:28:32,710 --> 01:28:34,587
[HORSE HOOVES CLOMPING]

1397
01:29:39,150 --> 01:29:40,265
Morning.

1398
01:30:16,670 --> 01:30:18,069
[BEEPING]

1399
01:30:18,750 --> 01:30:19,785
[SCREAMS]

1400
01:30:32,270 --> 01:30:33,669
[EXCLAIMING]

1401
01:31:00,390 --> 01:31:02,267
That's what I'm talking about.

1402
01:31:16,590 --> 01:31:18,660
Still feel like you're missing out?

1403
01:31:37,870 --> 01:31:38,939
[SCREAMS]

1404
01:31:44,270 --> 01:31:45,589
Fascist!

1405
01:32:01,550 --> 01:32:02,665
Hag!

1406
01:32:02,750 --> 01:32:03,944
[SCREAMS]

1407
01:32:20,390 --> 01:32:23,939
Stop! Stop this, please!

1408
01:32:24,590 --> 01:32:27,821
Let us stop this mindless violence.

1409
01:32:29,070 --> 01:32:30,981
Nicholas, my son.

1410
01:32:32,070 --> 01:32:35,858
You may not be a man of God,
but surely you're a man of peace.

1411
01:32:35,950 --> 01:32:41,468
I may not be a man of God, Reverend,
but I know right, and I know wrong,

1412
01:32:42,150 --> 01:32:44,618
and I have the good grace
to know which is which.

1413
01:32:44,710 --> 01:32:47,622
Oh, fuck off, Grasshopper.

1414
01:32:49,150 --> 01:32:50,549
No!

1415
01:32:51,710 --> 01:32:53,382
Jesus Christ!

1416
01:32:53,870 --> 01:32:55,781
Nicholas! Nicholas!

1417
01:32:56,310 --> 01:32:57,629
[GASPING]

1418
01:33:01,830 --> 01:33:03,548
I thought you was a goner.

1419
01:33:03,630 --> 01:33:05,268
Drop your weapons!

1420
01:33:05,870 --> 01:33:08,179
- Dr. Hatcher, no!
- Shut up, Danny.

1421
01:33:09,110 --> 01:33:12,500
I brought you into this world,
I think it's rather fitting

1422
01:33:12,590 --> 01:33:15,309
I should be the one to take you out of it.

1423
01:33:15,630 --> 01:33:19,305
You and your interfering little friend.

1424
01:33:19,750 --> 01:33:20,865
Now...

1425
01:33:25,070 --> 01:33:26,264
drop them.

1426
01:33:32,470 --> 01:33:33,903
[SCREAMING]

1427
01:33:42,110 --> 01:33:46,069
- You're a doctor, deal with it.
- Yeah, motherfucker.

1428
01:33:46,670 --> 01:33:48,900
- Danny, let's roll.
- What you thinking?

1429
01:33:50,830 --> 01:33:51,865
Pub?

1430
01:34:49,550 --> 01:34:51,427
Roy!

1431
01:34:52,110 --> 01:34:55,022
Somebody call the police!

1432
01:34:55,110 --> 01:34:56,225
Freeze!

1433
01:34:58,990 --> 01:35:01,709
Officers, arrest that man.

1434
01:35:02,150 --> 01:35:05,222
- Danny, step away from the Sergeant.
- No, Dad.

1435
01:35:05,590 --> 01:35:07,899
Danny, you'll do as you're told.

1436
01:35:07,990 --> 01:35:10,379
I'm not taking orders from you anymore.

1437
01:35:10,470 --> 01:35:13,826
- Officers, arrest these men!
- Wait, wait!

1438
01:35:13,910 --> 01:35:14,979
You can arrest us if you like.

1439
01:35:15,070 --> 01:35:17,584
You can throw us in prison and go back
to being blind, submissive slaves.

1440
01:35:17,670 --> 01:35:19,422
Or you can be real police officers,

1441
01:35:19,510 --> 01:35:21,626
and help us bring an end
to this absurd story.

1442
01:35:21,710 --> 01:35:23,780
What the fuck is he on about?

1443
01:35:23,870 --> 01:35:25,019
Fuck are you on about?

1444
01:35:25,110 --> 01:35:27,624
Have you ever wondered
why the crime rate in Sandford is so low?

1445
01:35:27,710 --> 01:35:31,339
- And yet the accident rate, it's so high?
- No. Yeah. What?

1446
01:35:31,430 --> 01:35:33,227
You've been brainwashed, Tony.

1447
01:35:33,310 --> 01:35:36,427
Brainwashed into naivety by an old man
with a murderous obsession.

1448
01:35:36,510 --> 01:35:41,220
- This is ridiculous.
- No, it's not, Dad. It's very unridiculous.

1449
01:35:41,310 --> 01:35:44,222
And it's only now that I'm starting to realise
how unridiculous it all is.

1450
01:35:44,310 --> 01:35:45,743
Silence, Danny!

1451
01:35:46,150 --> 01:35:48,869
- Think of your mother.
- Mum is dead, Dad.

1452
01:35:50,030 --> 01:35:53,261
For the first time in my life,
you know, I'm glad.

1453
01:35:53,350 --> 01:35:55,625
If she could see what you've become,

1454
01:35:55,710 --> 01:35:59,669
I think she'd probably kill herself
all over again.

1455
01:35:59,750 --> 01:36:01,263
Sorry, I am completely lost.

1456
01:36:01,350 --> 01:36:02,942
Sandford is a lie, Doris.

1457
01:36:03,030 --> 01:36:06,306
For the last 20 years, the village
has been controlled by Frank and the NWA.

1458
01:36:06,390 --> 01:36:08,745
They've lulled everyone
into thinking this is a perfect village

1459
01:36:08,830 --> 01:36:11,503
and killed anyone
who's threatened to change that.

1460
01:36:18,830 --> 01:36:20,821
I reckon he's got something there.

1461
01:36:22,230 --> 01:36:25,108
He says,
"He reckons you got something there."

1462
01:36:25,190 --> 01:36:26,384
I know.

1463
01:36:26,470 --> 01:36:29,587
You're not seriously gonna
believe this man, are you?

1464
01:36:29,670 --> 01:36:32,628
Are you? He isn't even from round here.

1465
01:36:36,390 --> 01:36:40,463
Maybe it's time to give it up, sir.

1466
01:36:42,070 --> 01:36:44,538
You incompetent flatfoots!

1467
01:36:53,310 --> 01:36:55,870
Officer Walker, stay here with Saxon
and hold everything down.

1468
01:36:55,950 --> 01:36:57,019
Fair enough.

1469
01:36:57,110 --> 01:36:59,066
Officers, let's go.

1470
01:36:59,990 --> 01:37:02,265
- What about Dad?
- He'll come round again.

1471
01:37:02,550 --> 01:37:04,302
Want anything from the shop?

1472
01:37:13,590 --> 01:37:15,103
[GUNS COCKING]

1473
01:37:21,350 --> 01:37:22,499
- What you thinking?
- Well...

1474
01:37:22,590 --> 01:37:24,501
We should strike now,
while we've got the element of surprise.

1475
01:37:24,590 --> 01:37:26,308
Longer we wait,
more time they've got to mobilise.

1476
01:37:26,390 --> 01:37:29,063
I say we go in through the front entrance,
take the place aisle by aisle.

1477
01:37:29,150 --> 01:37:30,947
They won't be expecting that.

1478
01:37:31,510 --> 01:37:33,148
Very good. What he said.

1479
01:37:35,270 --> 01:37:38,387
My, my. Here come the fuzz.

1480
01:37:40,510 --> 01:37:43,183
- Maybe they're not here.
- Wait here.

1481
01:37:43,270 --> 01:37:46,660
- Don't go in on your own.
- Don't worry, he knows what he's doing.

1482
01:37:49,470 --> 01:37:51,028
Okay. They're in.

1483
01:37:51,110 --> 01:37:54,102
You deal with the store.
I'll deal with the trolley boy.

1484
01:37:56,150 --> 01:37:57,299
[BOTH EXCLAIM]

1485
01:38:03,030 --> 01:38:07,342
No, listen. Wait, wait, wait, Michael,
wait, listen to me. Listen, listen.

1486
01:38:07,510 --> 01:38:09,978
Is this what you really, really want?

1487
01:38:10,270 --> 01:38:11,339
Yarp.

1488
01:38:11,670 --> 01:38:12,864
Suit yourself.

1489
01:38:21,190 --> 01:38:22,828
FISHER: Go, go, go.

1490
01:38:25,110 --> 01:38:27,146
Oh, come on.

1491
01:38:37,790 --> 01:38:38,859
[SCREAMS]

1492
01:38:38,950 --> 01:38:40,747
Andy!

1493
01:38:43,350 --> 01:38:46,228
It's all right, Andy. It's just Bolognese!

1494
01:39:23,830 --> 01:39:24,865
[GRUNTING]

1495
01:39:44,190 --> 01:39:46,067
- How's Lurch?
- He's in the freezer.

1496
01:39:46,150 --> 01:39:48,459
- Did you say, "Cool off"?
- No, I didn't say anything, actually.

1497
01:39:48,550 --> 01:39:50,188
Shame.

1498
01:39:50,270 --> 01:39:51,623
There was a bit earlier on that you missed

1499
01:39:51,710 --> 01:39:53,223
when I distracted him
with the cuddly monkey.

1500
01:39:53,310 --> 01:39:55,983
And then I said, "Playtime's over,"
and I hit him with the Peace Lily.

1501
01:39:56,070 --> 01:39:58,061
You're off the fucking chain!

1502
01:39:58,150 --> 01:40:01,506
- What's the situation?
- Two blokes and a fuckload of cutlery.

1503
01:40:01,590 --> 01:40:02,943
What do you reckon?

1504
01:40:06,150 --> 01:40:07,299
Idea.

1505
01:40:09,750 --> 01:40:11,388
[ALL YELLING]

1506
01:40:30,030 --> 01:40:31,463
Good work, everyone.

1507
01:40:31,550 --> 01:40:32,903
[SCREAMING]

1508
01:40:38,110 --> 01:40:39,509
[SQUEAKING]

1509
01:40:40,790 --> 01:40:43,668
- Nice one, Doris.
- Nothing like a bit of girl on girl.

1510
01:40:46,230 --> 01:40:48,221
Fruit attack!

1511
01:40:48,990 --> 01:40:51,709
Can you handle this, Sergeant Fisher?
We're gonna go after the big boss.

1512
01:40:51,790 --> 01:40:53,621
We're on it, Sergeant.

1513
01:40:54,070 --> 01:40:55,822
- Danny, let's rock.
- Angel!

1514
01:40:55,910 --> 01:40:57,582
Don't go being a twat now.

1515
01:40:57,870 --> 01:41:00,020
I wouldn't give you the satisfaction.

1516
01:41:06,950 --> 01:41:08,463
- We should get down there.
- How?

1517
01:41:08,550 --> 01:41:10,859
Skip.

1518
01:41:16,590 --> 01:41:19,502
- Head them off?
- Fuck, yeah.

1519
01:41:30,310 --> 01:41:33,825
- I'll drive.
- Shotgun! Punch that shit!

1520
01:41:35,990 --> 01:41:37,469
[SIREN WAILING]

1521
01:42:15,870 --> 01:42:17,349
Bang! Bang!

1522
01:42:23,070 --> 01:42:24,344
Swan!

1523
01:42:42,950 --> 01:42:44,019
Swan!

1524
01:42:48,030 --> 01:42:49,224
[CAWING]

1525
01:43:10,430 --> 01:43:14,423
Stay back! Or the ginger nut gets it!

1526
01:43:14,590 --> 01:43:15,864
[SCREAMS]

1527
01:43:16,270 --> 01:43:18,738
You little fucker!

1528
01:43:22,750 --> 01:43:24,024
[SCREAMS]

1529
01:43:53,070 --> 01:43:57,188
Get out of my village!

1530
01:44:02,910 --> 01:44:05,299
It's not your village anymore.

1531
01:44:21,470 --> 01:44:23,222
- You did good, kid.
- Ta.

1532
01:44:23,310 --> 01:44:25,460
- What's your name?
- Aaron A. Aaronson.

1533
01:44:25,830 --> 01:44:27,263
Sorry?

1534
01:44:29,150 --> 01:44:35,498
Angel!

1535
01:44:52,670 --> 01:44:53,944
It's over, Danny.

1536
01:44:55,310 --> 01:44:56,425
It's over.

1537
01:44:57,070 --> 01:44:58,788
[GROANING]

1538
01:45:00,070 --> 01:45:05,144
This really hurts.

1539
01:45:05,230 --> 01:45:10,429
I'm going to need some ice-cream.

1540
01:45:10,510 --> 01:45:13,547
Yeah, well, don't worry.
There's plenty of ice-cream at the station.

1541
01:45:13,630 --> 01:45:14,745
Isn't that right, Danny?

1542
01:45:14,830 --> 01:45:15,865
[GUN COCKING]

1543
01:45:15,950 --> 01:45:17,019
Stay back!

1544
01:45:17,110 --> 01:45:20,420
- Pack it in, Frank, you silly bastard!
- Now, now.

1545
01:45:20,750 --> 01:45:22,422
We don't want any more bloodshed.

1546
01:45:22,510 --> 01:45:25,149
Frank, this whole thing started
because you lost somebody you loved.

1547
01:45:25,230 --> 01:45:27,061
Don't expect me to believe
you'd let it end the same way.

1548
01:45:27,150 --> 01:45:29,584
I'll tell you how this is gonna end!

1549
01:46:05,270 --> 01:46:06,862
[FRANK SCREAMING]

1550
01:46:10,430 --> 01:46:12,500
I feel like I should say something smart.

1551
01:46:12,590 --> 01:46:15,263
You don't have to say anything at all.

1552
01:46:21,670 --> 01:46:22,659
[HELICOPTER WHIRRING]

1553
01:46:26,670 --> 01:46:29,946
Satisfactory conclusion
to the whole operation.

1554
01:46:30,030 --> 01:46:33,864
Now, my perfect Sunday would begin with...

1555
01:46:34,270 --> 01:46:35,942
[SKINNER GROANING]

1556
01:46:38,950 --> 01:46:40,349
CHIEF INSPECTOR:
What do you say, Nicholas?

1557
01:46:40,430 --> 01:46:42,546
We... We...
We have been trying to reach you for days.

1558
01:46:42,630 --> 01:46:45,667
- Yeah, well, I've been kind of busy.
- SERGEANT: We need you back.

1559
01:46:45,750 --> 01:46:49,425
The figures have gone a little squiffy
in your absence, it has to be said.

1560
01:46:49,510 --> 01:46:50,579
Come back to London.

1561
01:46:50,670 --> 01:46:53,787
Sandford's hardly a fitting place
for such an exceptional officer.

1562
01:46:53,870 --> 01:46:56,464
Yeah, well, the thing is, sir.

1563
01:46:57,350 --> 01:46:59,068
I kind of like it here.

1564
01:46:59,150 --> 01:47:02,381
Besides, we have to do
a considerable amount of paperwork.

1565
01:47:06,910 --> 01:47:08,025
[INAUDIBLE]

1566
01:47:31,550 --> 01:47:32,550
- Fuck's sake, Nick, this is gonna take ages.
- Yeah, it's gonna take all night.

1567
01:47:32,550 --> 01:47:33,539
FISHER: Well, good job
we've got the manpower, Andy?

1568
01:47:33,870 --> 01:47:37,943
Well, official vocab guidelines state
that we say "staffing," not "manpower,"

1569
01:47:38,030 --> 01:47:40,590
'cause "manpower's" a bit sexist.

1570
01:47:40,710 --> 01:47:42,268
[ALL EXCLAIMING]

1571
01:47:42,870 --> 01:47:44,622
You don't mind a bit
of manpower do you, Doris?

1572
01:47:44,710 --> 01:47:46,940
Oh, dirty bastard!

1573
01:47:48,630 --> 01:47:49,745
Andy!

1574
01:47:49,830 --> 01:47:51,786
You cheeky fucker!

1575
01:48:00,190 --> 01:48:02,021
You know what you are?

1576
01:48:02,830 --> 01:48:04,422
A bloody busybody!

1577
01:48:09,990 --> 01:48:12,185
No!

1578
01:48:18,110 --> 01:48:19,623
[DOOR LOCK BUZZING]

1579
01:48:24,870 --> 01:48:25,985
[TICKING]

1580
01:48:26,070 --> 01:48:27,219
Oh, God, no!

1581
01:48:49,550 --> 01:48:50,744
ANGEL: Danny!

1582
01:48:53,150 --> 01:48:54,219
Danny!

1583
01:48:55,230 --> 01:48:56,345
Oh, God.

1584
01:48:56,430 --> 01:48:57,988
Hold on, Danny, just hold on.

1585
01:48:58,070 --> 01:49:00,709
Hold on, it's gonna be fine.
It's gonna be fine.

1586
01:49:01,270 --> 01:49:03,943
Just hang on, hang on!

1587
01:49:04,390 --> 01:49:06,142
Everything's gonna be fine.

1588
01:49:07,350 --> 01:49:09,068
Everything's gonna be fine.

1589
01:49:09,510 --> 01:49:11,262
Everything's gonna be fine.

1590
01:49:11,990 --> 01:49:13,946
Everything's gonna be just fine.

1591
01:49:51,030 --> 01:49:52,065
Hope these are okay.

1592
01:49:55,030 --> 01:49:58,306
Yeah. They're lovely.

1593
01:50:07,470 --> 01:50:10,507
<i>- Any officers near the church?
- Go ahead, Doris.</i>

1594
01:50:10,590 --> 01:50:12,228
<i>Chief, we've had a report
of some hippy types</i>

1595
01:50:12,310 --> 01:50:14,665
<i>messing with the recycling bins
at the supermarket.</i>

1596
01:50:14,750 --> 01:50:16,388
<i>- Leave it with us.
- Righto.</i>

1597
01:50:16,470 --> 01:50:20,429
Sergeant Butterman,
little hand says it's time to rock and roll.

1598
01:50:20,630 --> 01:50:22,143
Bring the noise.

1599
